const neuroQuestions = [
  // BRAINSTEM LESIONS
  { id: 1, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 65-year-old woman is brought to the physician by her husband because of a 1-year history of progressive behavioral changes. He reports that she has become increasingly apathetic, makes inappropriate comments in public, and has difficulty with personal hygiene. She was previously a well-regarded school principal. Neurologic examination shows no focal motor or sensory deficits. MRI of the brain shows bilateral atrophy of a specific lobe. Which of the following brain regions is most likely affected?", a: "Frontal lobe. Diagnosis is frontotemporal dementia — classically presents with apathy, disinhibition, and personality change." },
  { id: 2, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 69-year-old woman with a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus is brought to the emergency department 2 hours after the sudden onset of difficulty speaking. Physical examination shows deviation of the tongue to the left when protruded. A cross-section of the medulla is shown. Which of the labeled areas most likely represents the location of the lesion?", a: "Medial medulla on the left side (medial medullary syndrome). Ipsilateral tongue deviation = medial medullary syndrome. Supplied by the paramedian branch of the anterior spinal artery (ASA)." },
  { id: 3, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 70-year-old man with a 20-year history of hypertension is brought to the emergency department because of the acute onset of left-sided facial droop, decreased hearing on the left, and numbness on the right side of his body. Physical examination shows inability to close the left eye, loss of the nasolabial fold on the left, decreased hearing on the left, and decreased pain and temperature sensation on the right side of the body. Which of the following arteries is most likely occluded?", a: "Anterior inferior cerebellar artery (AICA) — lateral pontine syndrome. Bell's palsy is the key detail. Mnemonic: FACIAL contains AICA backwards." },
  { id: 4, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 55-year-old woman is admitted to the hospital for management of hyponatremia (serum sodium 108 mEq/L). Her sodium is corrected to 130 mEq/L over 8 hours with hypertonic saline. Three days later, she develops quadriplegia, difficulty speaking, and difficulty swallowing. She can only communicate by blinking her eyes. MRI of the brain shows a symmetric lesion in the central pons. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Central pontine myelinolysis (osmotic demyelination syndrome) due to overly rapid correction of hyponatremia. Presents as locked-in syndrome (quadriplegia + aphonia + impaired horizontal eye movements). Do not confuse with cerebral edema from correcting hypernatremia too quickly." },
  { id: 5, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 78-year-old man with a history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of right-sided weakness. Physical examination shows that the left eye is deviated laterally and inferiorly with ptosis and a dilated pupil. Motor examination shows 2/5 strength in the right upper and lower extremities. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Weber syndrome — midbrain lesion resulting in ipsilateral CN III palsy (down and out + mydriasis) + contralateral hemiparesis (loss of crus cerebri). Lesion in paramedian branch of posterior cerebral artery (PCA)." },
  { id: 6, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 75-year-old woman died 8 years after having a cerebral infarction. At autopsy, examination of the brain shows an old infarct involving the right crus cerebri of the midbrain. Which of the following deficits was this patient most likely to have had during life?", a: "Spastic paralysis (upper motor neuron signs) on the left side of the body — contralateral to the crus cerebri lesion." },

  // MLF / INO / MS
  { id: 7, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 32-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 1-week history of urinary urgency and two episodes of urinary incontinence. She also reports difficulty seeing out of her right eye 6 months ago that resolved spontaneously. On examination, when she attempts to look to the right, the left eye fails to adduct past the midline. Convergence is intact bilaterally. An MRI of the brain shows multiple periventricular white matter lesions. Which of the following structures is most likely damaged?", a: "Left medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF). Dx is internuclear ophthalmoplegia (INO) in a patient with multiple sclerosis. The side that cannot adduct is the side of the pathology. Normal convergence rules out CN III lesion. MLF syndrome is pathognomonic for MS." },
  { id: 8, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 42-year-old woman comes to the physician because of 3 days of double vision. She reports that she can read books without difficulty. On examination, when she looks to the right, the left eye does not adduct past the midline. The right eye abducts normally but demonstrates nystagmus. Convergence is intact. Which of the following is the most likely location of the demyelinating plaque causing these symptoms?", a: "Left MLF (internuclear ophthalmoplegia). Normal convergence distinguishes this from a CN III lesion." },
  { id: 9, category: "Neuro", q: "A 27-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 2-week history of intermittent headaches and progressively worsening blurry vision in her left eye. She also reports that colors appear \"washed out\" when viewed with the left eye. Visual acuity is 20/40 in the left eye. Fundoscopic examination shows swelling of the left optic disc. A swinging flashlight test shows dilation of the left pupil when the light is moved from the right eye to the left eye. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Optic neuritis due to multiple sclerosis. Presents as blurry vision, change in color vision, or Marcus Gunn pupil (relative afferent pupillary defect)." },
  { id: 10, category: "Neuro", q: "A 34-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 1-week history of pain behind the left eye, progressive blurry vision, and weakness of the right arm and both legs. Fundoscopic examination shows swelling of the left optic disc. MRI of the brain shows multiple T2-weighted hyperintensities in the periventricular white matter and corpus callosum. A lumbar puncture shows oligoclonal bands in the CSF. Which of the following cells is the primary target of the immune-mediated attack in this disease?", a: "Oligodendrocytes. Dx is multiple sclerosis — T cell-mediated destruction of oligodendrocytes in CNS (in contrast, Schwann cell destruction in PNS is Guillain-Barre)." },
  { id: 11, category: "Neuro", q: "A 28-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 3-month history of urinary urgency, intermittent blurry vision, and difficulty walking. Examination shows decreased vibration sense in the toes bilaterally and a positive Romberg sign. She is unable to maintain balance with her eyes closed. MRI of the brain shows scattered white matter lesions. Which of the following spinal cord tracts is most likely damaged?", a: "Fasciculus gracilis of the dorsal columns (vibration/proprioception of the lower limbs). Dx is MS presenting with classic urge incontinence, optic neuritis, and (+) Romberg sign." },
  { id: 12, category: "Neuro", q: "A 34-year-old woman with a history of multiple sclerosis comes to the physician because of a 2-week history of severe shooting pain along her left cheek that is triggered by brushing her teeth. The episodes last a few seconds each. Neurologic examination is otherwise unremarkable. Which of the following regions of the CNS is the most likely location of the demyelinating plaque responsible for this patient's symptoms?", a: "Pons — where the trigeminal nerve (CN V) originates. This is an MS patient with trigeminal neuralgia-like presentation from a central demyelinating lesion." },

  // PARKINSON / BASAL GANGLIA
  { id: 13, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 74-year-old man is brought to the physician by his wife because of a 6-month history of progressive difficulty walking and a tremor in his right hand. Physical examination shows a low-frequency resting tremor of the right hand that diminishes with intentional movement. He has a shuffling gait and difficulty initiating movement. An MRI of the brain is performed. Which of the following brain structures is the most likely site of the pathology?", a: "Substantia nigra pars compacta (midbrain). Diagnosis is Parkinson disease — loss of dopaminergic neurons." },
  { id: 14, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 23-year-old woman is brought to the physician because of a 4-month history of progressive tremor in her right hand and difficulty with handwriting. Physical examination shows a resting tremor and cogwheel rigidity of the right upper extremity. Laboratory studies show elevated hepatic transaminases and decreased hematocrit. Slit-lamp examination shows golden-brown deposits at the periphery of both corneas. An MRI of the brain is obtained. Which of the following labeled structures is the most likely site of copper deposition?", a: "Putamen. Parkinsonism in a young patient is Wilson disease until proven otherwise; copper deposition occurs in basal ganglia, classically the putamen. Kayser-Fleischer rings on slit-lamp confirm the diagnosis." },
  { id: 15, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 41-year-old man is brought to the physician by his wife because of a 1-year history of involuntary jerking movements of his arms and legs and a 6-month history of progressive memory loss and personality changes. His father had a similar presentation and died at age 56. Physical examination shows rapid, irregular, purposeless movements of all extremities. MRI of the brain shows bilateral caudate atrophy with enlarged lateral ventricles. Testing for which of the following would most likely confirm the diagnosis?", a: "CAG trinucleotide repeat expansion on chromosome 4. Dx is Huntington disease — autosomal dominant, caudate nucleus degeneration. Chorea = fast, purposeless, jerky movements." },
  { id: 16, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 63-year-old man with a 25-year history of hypertension presents to the emergency department because of the sudden onset of wild, flinging movements of his left arm and leg that began 2 hours ago. Physical examination shows large-amplitude, involuntary ballistic movements of the left upper and lower extremities. CT of the head shows a small hemorrhage in the right brain. Which of the following structures is the most likely site of the hemorrhage?", a: "Right subthalamic nucleus. Dx is contralateral hemiballismus — large-amplitude involuntary flinging movements due to lesion of the subthalamic nucleus." },
  { id: 17, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 51-year-old woman presents to the emergency department because of the sudden onset of involuntary, irregular flailing movements of her right arm and leg. CT of the head shows a small hemorrhagic lesion. Which of the following structures is the most likely site of the lesion?", a: "Left subthalamic nucleus. Hemiballismus = contralateral subthalamic nucleus lesion." },
  { id: 18, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "An 18-year-old man is brought to the emergency department by his friends after he used an intravenous recreational drug sold as \"synthetic heroine\" at a party. He is alert and oriented but has difficulty walking. Physical examination shows muscular rigidity, bradykinesia, shuffling gait, and a resting tremor of both hands. He is afebrile and his pupils are equal and reactive. Which of the following brain structures is most likely affected?", a: "Substantia nigra. MPTP-induced Parkinsonism — MPTP is a contaminant in illicit synthetic opioids that selectively destroys dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra." },
  { id: 19, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 59-year-old man with Parkinson disease is evaluated during a follow-up visit. His physician explains that the loss of dopaminergic neurons in his substantia nigra pars compacta is most likely to result in disinhibition of which of the following brain structures?", a: "Striatum (caudate + putamen). Loss of dopaminergic input from the substantia nigra leads to dysregulation of the basal ganglia circuit via the striatum." },

  // INTERNAL CAPSULE
  { id: 20, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 78-year-old man with a 30-year history of poorly controlled hypertension is brought to the emergency department because of sudden onset of left-sided weakness 1 hour ago. Physical examination shows 1/5 strength in the left upper and lower extremities with increased tone and a positive Babinski sign on the left. Sensation is intact throughout. CT of the head shows a small lacunar infarct. Which of the following is the most likely location of this infarct?", a: "Posterior limb of internal capsule. Lenticulostriate vessels supply the internal capsule; chronic HTN causes lipohyalinosis. Posterior limb infarcts produce 'pure motor' hemiparesis (contralateral), with no sensory deficits." },

  // CRANIAL NERVES
  { id: 21, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 32-year-old woman presents to the physician because of a 1-week history of an expanding circular rash on her right forearm after a hiking trip in Connecticut. She now reports inability to close her left eye and difficulty drinking from a glass. Physical examination shows left-sided facial droop involving the forehead. Which of the following nerves is most likely affected?", a: "Facial nerve (CN VII). Bell's palsy secondary to Lyme disease (Borrelia burgdorferi). The forehead involvement indicates a lower motor neuron lesion." },
  { id: 22, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 76-year-old man with a history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation is brought to the emergency department because of difficulty swallowing that began suddenly 3 hours ago. On examination, when the patient says \"Ahh,\" the uvula deviates to the left. Which of the following nerves is most likely damaged?", a: "Right vagus nerve (CN X). Vagus nerve lesion causes the uvula to deviate to the contralateral side (away from the lesion) because the intact side pulls it over." },
  { id: 23, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 35-year-old woman comes to the physician because of sudden complete hearing loss in her left ear. She denies any vertigo, tinnitus, or neurologic symptoms. Otoscopic examination is unremarkable. Weber test lateralizes to the right ear. Rinne test shows air conduction greater than bone conduction bilaterally. Which of the following cranial nerves is most likely damaged?", a: "Left vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII). Sensorineural hearing loss — Weber lateralizes to the unaffected ear; Rinne shows AC > BC bilaterally." },
  { id: 24, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 47-year-old man comes to the physician because of severe, sharp pain over the right cheek that is triggered by chewing. The pain is localized to the area just lateral to the nose. Physical examination shows tenderness to palpation over the right maxillary region. The nerve supplying sensation to this area exits the skull through which of the following foramina?", a: "Foramen rotundum — exit point for the maxillary branch (V2) of the trigeminal nerve. Mnemonic: Standing Room Only = Superior orbital fissure (V1), foramen Rotundum (V2), foramen Ovale (V3)." },
  { id: 25, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 19-year-old man presents with a 3-day history of inability to close his right eye and drooping of the right side of his mouth. He had an upper respiratory infection 2 weeks ago. He also reports that everyday sounds seem uncomfortably loud in his right ear. Which of the following best explains the hyperacusis?", a: "CN VII (facial nerve) innervates the stapedius muscle, which normally dampens sounds by stabilizing the stapes. Loss of stapedius function due to facial nerve palsy results in ipsilateral hyperacusis." },
  { id: 26, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 54-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 4-day history of progressively worsening hoarseness and difficulty swallowing. On examination, when the patient says \"Ahh,\" the left side of the palate fails to elevate and the uvula deviates to the right. Which of the following nerves is most likely damaged?", a: "Left vagus nerve (CN X). Failure of elevation of the ipsilateral palate causes the uvula to deviate to the contralateral (intact) side." },
  { id: 27, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 24-year-old man comes to the physician because of decreased taste sensation on the left side of the front of his tongue that he noticed 2 days ago. He denies any facial weakness or hearing changes. Which of the following nerves is most likely damaged?", a: "Left facial nerve (CN VII) — carries taste from the anterior 2/3 of the tongue via the chorda tympani." },
  { id: 28, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 45-year-old man presents with difficulty swallowing and a 1-week history of a hoarse voice. On examination, the uvula deviates to the right when the patient says \"Ahh.\" The physician is concerned about involvement of the tongue. Which of the following tongue muscles is most likely affected given the nerve involved?", a: "Palatoglossus (innervated by CN X, the vagus nerve). All other tongue muscles are innervated by CN XII (hypoglossal)." },
  { id: 29, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A medical student is studying the thalamus and its relay functions. She notes that nearly all sensory information is relayed through the thalamus before reaching the cortex. Which of the following cranial nerves is notable for being the only one that does NOT relay sensory information through the thalamus?", a: "Olfactory nerve (CN I) — the only cranial nerve that does not relay through the thalamus." },
  { id: 30, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 59-year-old woman with a history of metastatic breast cancer presents with the acute onset of inability to feel a cotton wisp touched to the right cornea. The physician suspects metastases to a cranial nerve exit point. Which of the following foramina is the most likely site of the metastasis?", a: "Superior orbital fissure — exit point for the ophthalmic branch (V1) of the trigeminal nerve, which carries the afferent limb of the corneal reflex." },

  // VASCULATURE
  { id: 31, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 48-year-old woman with a history of autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease presents to the emergency department with the worst headache of her life and a dilated right pupil that is unreactive to light. The right eye is deviated downward and outward. CT of the head shows subarachnoid hemorrhage. An aneurysm of which of the following vessels is most likely responsible for her presentation?", a: "Posterior communicating artery (PCoM). PCoM aneurysms compress CN III, causing ipsilateral mydriasis and \"down and out\" eye. ADPKD is a risk factor for berry aneurysms." },
  { id: 32, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "An 82-year-old woman with a history of atrial fibrillation and hypertension is brought to the emergency department because she suddenly became unable to move any part of her body except her eyes. She is fully conscious and able to communicate by blinking. MRA of the brain is obtained. Which of the following arteries is most likely occluded?", a: "Basilar artery — resulting in locked-in syndrome (intact consciousness with quadriplegia, aphonia, and intact vertical eye movements only)." },
  { id: 33, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 68-year-old man with a history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and a 40-pack-year smoking history presents with the sudden onset of painless loss of vision in the right eye. Fundoscopic examination shows a pale retina with a \"cherry red spot\" at the macula. A carotid Doppler ultrasound shows 80% stenosis of the right internal carotid artery. Which of the following arteries is most likely occluded?", a: "Central retinal artery (a branch of the ophthalmic artery, which is a branch of the internal carotid artery). Carotid plaque embolized to the retinal vasculature." },
  { id: 34, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 32-year-old man comes to the physician because of recurrent episodes of dizziness and near-syncope over the past month, particularly when exercising his right arm. Physical examination shows blood pressure of 130/80 mm Hg in the left arm and 100/60 mm Hg in the right arm. An angiogram of the aortic arch and great vessels is obtained. Retrograde flow through which of the following vessels is most likely responsible for his symptoms?", a: "Right vertebral artery. Dx is subclavian steal syndrome — proximal stenosis of the subclavian artery causes retrograde flow through the ipsilateral vertebral artery (first branch of subclavian), \"stealing\" blood from the posterior circulation." },

  // CEREBELLUM
  { id: 35, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 34-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after a boating accident in which she sustained blunt trauma to the head. She has normal muscle strength bilaterally, but when asked to touch her nose and then the examiner's finger, she repeatedly overshoots and undershoots on the right side. A sagittal cross-section of the brain is shown. Which of the following labeled structures most likely corresponds to the site of her injury?", a: "Right cerebellar hemisphere. Cerebellar injuries cause ipsilateral dysmetria (past-pointing). The cerebellar vermis, in contrast, would cause truncal ataxia." },
  { id: 36, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 44-year-old man with a long history of alcohol use disorder comes to the physician because of difficulty walking that has been worsening over the past several months. Physical examination shows a wide-based, unsteady gait with tendency to fall to the right. Romberg sign is negative. Which of the following is the most likely location of the pathology?", a: "Right cerebellar hemisphere. Cerebellar lesions cause ipsilateral deficits. Negative Romberg sign points to cerebellar rather than dorsal column etiology on USMLE." },
  { id: 37, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 44-year-old man presents with a 6-month history of progressively worsening unsteady gait and left-sided intention tremor that worsens as his hand approaches a target. His speech is slow and scanning. Which of the following brain areas is most likely damaged?", a: "Left cerebellar hemisphere. Cerebellar lesions lead to ipsilateral neurologic signs (unlike most brain lesions, which are contralateral)." },

  // PERIPHERAL NERVES
  { id: 38, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 26-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after being slashed on the upper arm during a bar fight. Physical examination shows a deep laceration on the posterior aspect of the right upper arm. The right hand is held with the wrist flexed and fingers drooping, and the forearm is pronated. He is unable to extend the wrist or fingers. Which of the following nerves is most likely damaged?", a: "Radial nerve (posterior cord of brachial plexus). Wrist drop + inability to extend fingers + pronated forearm is classic for radial nerve injury." },
  { id: 39, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 45-year-old man presents to the emergency department after falling off a ladder and sustaining a midshaft fracture of the right humerus. He is unable to extend his right wrist and has decreased sensation over the dorsal surface of the hand between the first and second digits. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?", a: "Radial nerve. Midshaft humerus fractures classically injure the radial nerve as it travels in the spiral groove, causing wrist drop and sensory loss over the anatomical snuffbox." },
  { id: 40, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 7-year-old boy is brought to the emergency department after falling off monkey bars. Radiography shows a displaced supracondylar fracture of the right humerus. After the fracture is reduced and casted, the patient is unable to make an \"OK\" sign with his right hand and has decreased sensation over the palmar surface of the first three digits. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?", a: "Median nerve. Supracondylar fractures of the humerus classically injure the median nerve (or brachial artery)." },
  { id: 41, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 22-year-old man presents to the emergency department after falling on his elbow while skateboarding. Radiography shows a fracture of the medial epicondyle of the right humerus. He reports tingling in his 4th and 5th digits and is unable to abduct his fingers. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?", a: "Ulnar nerve. Medial epicondylar fractures injure the ulnar nerve, causing sensory deficits in digits 4-5 and weakness of interossei (finger abduction/adduction)." },
  { id: 42, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 70-year-old woman presents to the emergency department after falling and landing on her right shoulder. Radiography shows a fracture of the surgical neck of the right humerus. She is unable to abduct her right arm beyond 15 degrees and has decreased sensation over the lateral aspect of the right deltoid. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?", a: "Axillary nerve. Surgical neck of humerus fractures and anterior shoulder dislocations can injure the axillary nerve, which innervates the deltoid and teres minor." },
  { id: 43, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 52-year-old woman presents for a follow-up visit 2 weeks after a left radical mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection. She reports difficulty raising her left arm above her head. Physical examination shows the left scapula protrudes prominently from the back when she pushes against a wall. Which of the following nerves was most likely injured during surgery?", a: "Long thoracic nerve, which innervates the serratus anterior muscle. Injury causes a winged scapula." },
  { id: 44, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 25-year-old man presents to the physician because of difficulty walking after twisting his ankle during a basketball game. Physical examination shows inability to plantarflex the right foot and inability to invert the right foot. He is unable to stand on his tiptoes on the right side. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?", a: "Tibial nerve. Innervates the muscles responsible for plantar flexion and inversion of the foot." },
  { id: 45, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 25-year-old man presents to the physician because of difficulty walking. He reports that he has to lift his right foot higher than normal when walking to prevent his toes from dragging on the ground. Physical examination shows inability to dorsiflex and evert the right foot. Which of the following nerves is most likely injured?", a: "Common peroneal (fibular) nerve. Injury causes foot drop (impaired dorsiflexion) and loss of eversion." },
  { id: 46, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 15-year-old girl presents to the physician because of a 2-month history of intermittent pain and tingling in her right hand that occurs when wearing a heavy backpack. Symptoms resolve within 5 minutes of removing the backpack. Physical examination is unremarkable. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Thoracic outlet syndrome due to compression by the first cervical rib. The weight of the backpack compresses neurovascular structures at the thoracic outlet." },
  { id: 47, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 32-year-old woman who works as an office assistant presents with a 3-month history of numbness and tingling in the thumb, index finger, and middle finger of her right hand. She also reports weakness when gripping objects. Sensation is intact over the dorsum of the hand. Tinel sign is positive at the wrist. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?", a: "Electrophysiological testing (nerve conduction studies). For carpal tunnel syndrome, Tinel sign and Phalen maneuver alone are insufficient for definitive diagnosis on NBME." },

  // SPINAL CORD
  { id: 48, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 45-year-old man died several years after a boating accident. At autopsy, a spinal cord cross-section is stained with a myelin stain and shows bilateral loss of staining in the fasciculus gracilis of the dorsal columns. Which of the following deficits was this patient most likely to have had during life?", a: "Loss of vibration and proprioception in the lower limbs. Fasciculus gracilis carries dorsal column sensory information from the lower extremities (below T6). Fasciculus cuneatus does the same for the upper limbs." },
  { id: 49, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 43-year-old woman presents with a 2-week history of inability to sense pain and temperature over her right lower extremity. Vibration and proprioception are intact. A spinal cord cross-section is shown. Which of the following labeled areas most likely represents the location of the lesion?", a: "Left spinothalamic tract. The spinothalamic tract crosses at the level of the spinal cord (within 1-2 segments), so a lesion of the left spinothalamic tract causes contralateral (right-sided) loss of pain and temperature." },
  { id: 50, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 24-year-old man presents to the emergency department 2 days after the onset of progressive weakness and sensory changes. He recently recovered from a viral illness. Physical examination shows loss of motor function and vibration/proprioception in the left leg, and loss of pain and temperature sensation in the right leg. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Brown-Sequard syndrome (hemisection of the spinal cord). Ipsilateral motor loss + ipsilateral dorsal column loss (vibration/proprioception) + contralateral spinothalamic loss (pain/temperature). Can occur from stab wounds, MS, or viral infection." },
  { id: 51, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 33-year-old woman presents with a 1-week history of progressive right-sided weakness, left-sided inability to sense temperature and pain, decreased vibratory sensation over the right foot, brisk right-sided reflexes, and a right-sided Babinski sign. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Brown-Sequard syndrome (right-sided spinal cord hemisection). Ipsilateral UMN signs (brisk reflexes, Babinski) + ipsilateral vibration loss + contralateral pain/temp loss." },
  { id: 52, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 67-year-old man with a long history of cervical spondylosis presents to the emergency department after being rear-ended in a motor vehicle accident. He reports neck pain and weakness in all four extremities, but the weakness is significantly worse in the upper extremities than the lower extremities. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Central cord syndrome. Occurs with hyperextension injuries in patients with pre-existing cervical spondylosis. Upper extremity weakness > lower extremity weakness because the corticospinal tract fibers for the arms pass more centrally in the cervical cord." },
  { id: 53, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 69-year-old man with a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and peripheral vascular disease presents with the sudden onset of bilateral leg weakness and loss of pain and temperature sensation below the level of the nipples. He has intact vibration sense and proprioception in both legs. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Anterior cord syndrome. Dorsal columns are spared (vibration/proprioception intact), while the anterior 2/3 of the cord is infarcted (loss of motor + spinothalamic). Often due to atherosclerosis of the anterior spinal artery." },
  { id: 54, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 23-year-old man presents with progressive difficulty walking and unsteadiness. He has a history of multiple sexual partners and inconsistent condom use. Physical examination shows loss of vibration sense and proprioception in both lower extremities. Motor function and pain/temperature sensation are intact. An RPR test is positive. A spinal cord cross-section stained with myelin stain shows loss of staining limited to the dorsal columns. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Tabes dorsalis (neurosyphilis). Treponema pallidum causes selective demyelination of the dorsal columns, resulting in isolated loss of vibration and proprioception with intact motor and pain/temperature function." },
  { id: 55, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 31-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a motorcycle accident. MRI of the spine shows a lesion centered in the anterior white commissure of the spinal cord at the cervical level. Which of the following neurologic deficits is this patient most likely to develop?", a: "Bilateral loss of pain and temperature sensation in a cape-like distribution over the upper extremities. Dx is syringomyelia (lesion of the anterior white commissure where the spinothalamic fibers cross). Associated with Chiari I malformation." },
  { id: 56, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 54-year-old man presents with a 6-month history of progressive difficulty walking and using his hands. Physical examination shows clonus and a positive Babinski sign in the left foot, fasciculations in the right hand and both calves, muscle atrophy in the right hand, and brisk reflexes throughout. Sensation is intact. Serum creatine kinase is mildly elevated. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS). Hallmark is combination of UMN signs (clonus, Babinski, brisk reflexes) AND LMN signs (fasciculations, atrophy) with NO sensory abnormalities. If sensory findings are present, it's NOT ALS." },
  { id: 57, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 55-year-old man who recently immigrated from Albania presents to a physician for the first time. Physical examination shows that his left leg is significantly smaller in circumference than the right, with markedly decreased muscle bulk and diminished motor function. Deep tendon reflexes are absent in the left lower extremity. There are no sensory deficits. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Polio (poliomyelitis). Poliovirus infects and destroys the anterior horn motor neurons of the spinal cord, causing LMN-type deficits (decreased muscle bulk, absent reflexes) without sensory loss." },
  { id: 58, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 40-year-old man comes to the physician because of a 4-month history of progressive weakness in his hands and legs. Physical examination shows fasciculations and muscle atrophy in both hands, spasticity and hyperreflexia in both lower extremities, and a positive Babinski sign bilaterally. Sensation is intact throughout. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS). The combination of upper motor neuron (spasticity, hyperreflexia, Babinski) and lower motor neuron (fasciculations, atrophy) findings with NO sensory deficits is pathognomonic." },

  // SPINE
  { id: 59, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 22-year-old man is scheduled to undergo a laminectomy for a herniated disc. An illustration of a lumbar vertebra is shown. Which of the following labeled structures should the surgeon remove to access the spinal canal?", a: "Lamina — the posterior arch of the vertebra that forms the roof of the spinal canal." },
  { id: 60, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 17-year-old boy is undergoing spinal surgery. A needle is inserted posteriorly between the L3 and L4 vertebral arches to access the spinal canal. After penetrating the skin, subcutaneous tissue, and supraspinous ligament, which of the following ligaments must the needle traverse to reach the spinal canal?", a: "Ligamentum flavum — connects the laminae of adjacent vertebrae and is the last ligament traversed before entering the epidural space." },
  { id: 61, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 24-year-old man presents with severe lower back pain radiating down his left leg after lifting heavy furniture. MRI shows a posterolateral herniation of the L4-L5 intervertebral disc. Which of the following spinal ligaments is being pushed into the spinal root nerves?", a: "Posterior longitudinal ligament — runs along the posterior aspect of the vertebral bodies within the spinal canal, directly anterior to the disc herniation." },
  { id: 62, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 63-year-old man presents with a 3-week history of pain radiating from his lower back down the front of his right thigh, across the knee, and along the medial aspect of the leg and foot. Physical examination shows decreased patellar reflex on the right. Compression of a nerve root at which of the following intervertebral levels is the most likely cause of his symptoms?", a: "L3-L4. This dermatome pattern (anterior thigh, medial leg, medial foot) and loss of patellar reflex (L3/L4) localizes to the L3-L4 level." },
  { id: 63, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 32-year-old woman at 28 weeks gestation presents with intensely pruritic vesicles distributed in a band around her umbilicus. A skin biopsy shows subepidermal blisters with eosinophilic infiltrate. The sensory innervation to this region is carried by which of the following dermatomes?", a: "T10. The umbilicus is a classic landmark for the T10 dermatome." },
  { id: 64, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 48-year-old man accidentally burns his thumb while cooking. He notes sharp pain at the site of the burn. The pain sensation from his thumb is primarily carried by which of the following dermatomes?", a: "C6. Dermatome landmarks: lateral digits (thumb, index) = C6; middle finger = C7; medial digits (ring, pinky) = C8." },
  { id: 65, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "An 81-year-old woman presents with a 6-month history of progressive difficulty fastening buttons and numbness in both 5th fingers. Physical examination shows weakness of the intrinsic muscles of both hands and decreased sensation over the medial aspect of both hands. Cervical MRI shows foraminal narrowing. At which of the following spinal levels is the compression most likely occurring?", a: "C7-T1. The intrinsic hand muscles are supplied by C8-T1 (ulnar nerve), and the 5th digit is the C8 dermatome." },
  { id: 66, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 44-year-old man presents with a 2-week history of lower back pain and progressive difficulty urinating. He reports numbness over his buttocks and perineum. Physical examination shows decreased anal sphincter tone, absent ankle jerk reflexes, and urinary retention. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Cauda equina syndrome — compression of the bundle of spinal nerve roots below the conus medullaris. Characterized by saddle anesthesia, late urinary retention, and LMN signs (absent reflexes)." },
  { id: 67, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 44-year-old man presents with sudden onset of severe lower back pain, perianal numbness, and urinary and fecal incontinence that developed acutely. Physical examination shows decreased perianal sensation and absent bulbocavernosus reflex. Bladder catheterization yields 600 mL of urine. MRI of the lumbar spine shows a lesion at the L1-L2 level. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Conus medullaris syndrome — damage to the terminal end of the spinal cord. Characterized by early-onset urinary and fecal incontinence, perianal anesthesia, and symmetric findings. In contrast, cauda equina has later onset of bladder symptoms and asymmetric findings." },

  // STROKES
  { id: 68, category: "Neuro", q: "A 77-year-old man with a history of hypertension and diabetes presents to the emergency department with the sudden onset of drooping of the left eyelid, constriction of the left pupil, hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, and decreased pain and temperature sensation on the left side of his face and the right side of his body. Which of the following arteries is most likely occluded?", a: "Left posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA). This is lateral medullary syndrome (Wallenberg syndrome): ipsilateral Horner syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis) + dysphagia/hoarseness + ipsilateral face and contralateral body pain/temperature loss. Mnemonic: PICA-chew = dysphagia." },
  { id: 69, category: "Neuro", q: "A 69-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents to the emergency department because of sudden onset of hoarse voice and difficulty swallowing. Physical examination shows decreased pain and temperature sensation on the right side of his face and the left side of his body. The gag reflex is absent on the right. Which of the following is the most likely location of the lesion?", a: "Right lateral medulla (PICA territory). Lateral medullary syndrome = PICAchew = dysphagia/hoarseness + crossed pain/temperature deficits +/- Horner syndrome." },
  { id: 70, category: "Neuro", q: "A 54-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department because of the sudden onset of difficulty speaking 3 hours ago. She appears frustrated and speaks in short, effortful phrases with poor grammar, but she is able to understand questions and follow commands. Physical examination shows weakness of the lower two-thirds of the right side of her face. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis, and which artery is involved?", a: "Broca aphasia due to occlusion of the left middle cerebral artery. Broca area is in the posterior inferior frontal lobe. Non-fluent, telegraphic speech with intact comprehension. Repetition is impaired." },
  { id: 71, category: "Neuro", q: "A 65-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of weakness in his left leg. Physical examination shows blood pressure of 140/100 mm Hg, 2/5 strength in the left lower extremity with brisk reflexes, and a positive Babinski sign on the left. Upper extremity strength and facial movements are normal. Which of the following arteries is the most likely site of the occlusion?", a: "Right anterior cerebral artery (ACA). ACA supplies the medial surface of the frontal and parietal lobes, which correspond to the motor and sensory cortex for the lower extremity." },
  { id: 72, category: "Neuro", q: "A 65-year-old man with a history of type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia presents with the sudden onset of inability to move all four extremities. He is unable to speak but is fully alert and can communicate by blinking his eyes. He can move his eyes vertically but not horizontally. Which of the following structures is the most likely site of the lesion?", a: "Pons (ventral portion). This is locked-in syndrome caused by basilar artery stroke. The patient is conscious (reticular activating system is intact) but has quadriplegia and inability to speak, with only vertical eye movements preserved." },
  { id: 73, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old man presents to the physician because of a 2-week history of constant, severe, burning pain in his left arm and hand. His medical history is significant for a stroke 5 months ago that resulted in decreased sensation on the left side of his body. The pain is disproportionate to any stimulus and is extremely distressing. MRI shows an old infarct. Which of the following brain structures is the most likely site of the lesion?", a: "Right thalamus. This is thalamic pain syndrome (Dejerine-Roussy syndrome) — severe contralateral pain that develops months after a thalamic stroke. A high-yield post-stroke cause of chronic pain." },
  { id: 74, category: "Neuro", q: "A 54-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of difficulty recognizing faces and objects by sight. He can identify objects when he touches them. Neurologic examination shows a left homonymous hemianopsia. MRI of the brain shows an acute infarct. Which of the following arteries is the most likely site of the occlusion?", a: "Posterior cerebral artery (PCA). Prosopagnosia (inability to recognize faces) and visual agnosia (inability to recognize objects by sight) are associated with occipital lobe lesions supplied by the PCA." },
  { id: 75, category: "Neuro", q: "A 71-year-old woman presents to the emergency department 4 hours after the acute onset of difficulty writing, performing calculations, distinguishing her right from her left, and identifying her own fingers when asked. MRI of the brain shows an acute infarct in the left parietal lobe. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Gerstmann syndrome — agraphia, acalculia, finger agnosia, and left-right disorientation due to a lesion of the angular gyrus of the dominant (left) parietal lobe." },
  { id: 76, category: "Neuro", q: "An 81-year-old man dies 3 days after a large left middle cerebral artery stroke. At autopsy, the area of infarction is being cleared by cells that are positive for CD68. Which of the following cell types is primarily responsible for clearing the necrotic tissue?", a: "Microglial cells — the resident macrophages of the CNS. They are derived from mesoderm and function as the primary phagocytes of the central nervous system." },
  { id: 77, category: "Neuro", q: "A 62-year-old woman with a history of hypertension presents to the emergency department with the sudden onset of hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, drooping of the right eyelid, constriction of the right pupil, and decreased sweating on the right side of the face. Physical examination also shows decreased pain and temperature sensation on the right side of the face and left side of the body. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Lateral medullary syndrome (Wallenberg syndrome) due to PICA infarct. Ipsilateral Horner syndrome + dysphagia/hoarseness + crossed sensory deficits. Mnemonic: PICAchew = dysphagia." },
  { id: 78, category: "Neuro", q: "A 68-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of right-sided facial droop involving the entire right side of the face, including the forehead. He also has decreased hearing on the right. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Lateral pontine syndrome due to AICA (anterior inferior cerebellar artery) infarct. Ipsilateral Bell palsy (entire face) and hearing loss are key features. Mnemonic: FACIAL spelled backwards contains AICA." },
  { id: 79, category: "Neuro", q: "A 72-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of tongue deviation to the right when protruded, and left-sided hemiparesis. Sensory examination shows decreased proprioception on the left. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Medial medullary syndrome due to occlusion of the paramedian branch of the anterior spinal artery. Ipsilateral tongue deviation (CN XII) + contralateral motor weakness and proprioceptive loss." },
  { id: 80, category: "Neuro", q: "A 70-year-old man with a history of atrial fibrillation is brought to the emergency department because he suddenly became unable to move or speak. He is fully conscious and can communicate only by blinking his eyes and moving his eyes vertically. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Locked-in syndrome due to basilar artery stroke. Consciousness is preserved, but the patient has quadriplegia and anarthria with only vertical eye movements intact." },
  { id: 81, category: "Neuro", q: "A 72-year-old man with a 25-year history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of left-sided hemiparesis. Physical examination shows 2/5 strength on the left side with no sensory deficits. CT of the head shows a small lacunar infarct in the right posterior limb of the internal capsule. Which of the following best describes the pathogenesis of this type of infarct?", a: "Lipohyalinosis of the lenticulostriate arteries due to chronic hypertension. Lacunar infarcts of the posterior limb of the internal capsule produce pure motor hemiparesis (contralateral)." },
  { id: 82, category: "Neuro", q: "A 68-year-old woman with a history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of numbness and tingling over her entire left side. She has no motor deficits. CT of the head shows a small lacunar infarct. Which of the following thalamic nuclei is the most likely site of the infarct?", a: "Ventral posterolateral (VPL) and/or ventral posteromedial (VPM) nuclei of the thalamus. Thalamic lacunar infarcts produce pure sensory deficits (contralateral). VPL relays sensation from the body; VPM from the face." },
  { id: 83, category: "Neuro", q: "A 60-year-old man presents with a 3-month history of severe, constant burning pain in his right arm and leg. His medical history is significant for a stroke 6 months ago that initially presented with right-sided numbness. The pain is described as excruciating and is exacerbated by light touch. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Thalamic pain syndrome (Dejerine-Roussy syndrome). Severe contralateral neuropathic pain that develops weeks to months after a thalamic stroke." },
  { id: 84, category: "Neuro", q: "A 25-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a high-speed motor vehicle accident. He is unresponsive with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 5. CT of the head shows no midline shift, no epidural or subdural hematoma, and no subarachnoid hemorrhage. However, MRI shows multiple small hemorrhagic lesions at the grey-white matter junction throughout both hemispheres. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Diffuse axonal injury — caused by rotational shearing forces during rapid deceleration. Classically affects the grey-white matter junction, corpus callosum, and brainstem." },
  { id: 85, category: "Neuro", q: "A 62-year-old man presents 6 hours after the sudden onset of right-sided weakness and difficulty speaking. His speech is fluent but contains nonsensical words, and he is unable to follow commands. He also has right-sided homonymous hemianopsia and right-sided hemiparesis. An MRI shows an acute infarct in the territory of the left middle cerebral artery. Which of the following combinations of deficits is most characteristic of this type of stroke?", a: "MCA stroke (dominant hemisphere): contralateral face and arm > leg weakness + contralateral sensory loss + Broca aphasia (if inferior frontal) and/or Wernicke aphasia (if superior temporal) + contralateral homonymous hemianopsia." },
  { id: 86, category: "Neuro", q: "A 70-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents with sudden weakness of his right leg. Physical examination shows 2/5 strength in the right lower extremity, with intact upper extremity strength and normal facial movements. There is also decreased sensation over the right leg. Which of the following vascular territories is the most likely site of the infarct?", a: "Anterior cerebral artery (ACA). The ACA supplies the medial frontal and parietal cortex, which maps to the leg region of the motor and sensory homunculus." },
  { id: 87, category: "Neuro", q: "A 74-year-old woman presents with the sudden onset of inability to see objects in her left visual field from either eye. She also reports that she can still see fine detail when looking straight ahead. MRI of the brain shows an acute infarct in the right occipital lobe. Which of the following best describes her visual field defect?", a: "Left homonymous hemianopsia with macular sparing. PCA stroke produces contralateral homonymous hemianopsia, and the macula is often spared because it receives dual blood supply from both PCA and MCA." },

  // APHASIA
  { id: 88, category: "Neuro", q: "A 58-year-old man is brought to the emergency department because of the sudden onset of difficulty speaking. He appears frustrated and speaks in short, effortful, grammatically incomplete phrases such as \"want... water.\" He can understand spoken language and follow commands but is unable to repeat phrases when asked. MRI shows an infarct in the left posterior inferior frontal lobe. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Broca aphasia. Non-fluent, telegraphic speech with intact comprehension but impaired repetition. Located in the posterior, lateral, inferior frontal lobe (Broca area)." },
  { id: 89, category: "Neuro", q: "A 65-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department because of the sudden onset of difficulty speaking. She speaks in long, fluent sentences that contain many nonexistent words and make no sense. She is unable to follow commands or comprehend spoken language. She is unable to repeat phrases when asked. MRI shows an infarct in the left posterior superior temporal gyrus. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Wernicke aphasia. Fluent but nonsensical speech (\"word salad\") with impaired comprehension and impaired repetition. Located in the superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke area)." },
  { id: 90, category: "Neuro", q: "A 60-year-old man presents with difficulty repeating phrases after an ischemic stroke. His speech is fluent, and his comprehension is intact. He can name objects and carry on a conversation, but when asked to repeat \"no ifs, ands, or buts,\" he is unable to do so. MRI shows a lesion in a white matter tract connecting two cortical regions. Which of the following structures is most likely damaged?", a: "Arcuate fasciculus (connecting Broca and Wernicke areas). This is conduction aphasia — fluent speech, intact comprehension, but impaired repetition." },
  { id: 91, category: "Neuro", q: "A 62-year-old man presents after a stroke with effortful, non-fluent speech and difficulty getting his words out. However, when the examiner says a phrase, the patient is able to repeat it accurately. Comprehension is intact. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Transcortical motor aphasia. Sounds like Broca aphasia (non-fluent, effortful speech) but repetition is INTACT — this is the key distinguishing feature." },
  { id: 92, category: "Neuro", q: "A 68-year-old woman presents after a stroke with fluent, nonsensical speech and poor comprehension. However, she is able to repeat phrases when asked. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Transcortical sensory aphasia. Sounds like Wernicke aphasia (fluent nonsensical speech, poor comprehension) but repetition is INTACT." },

  // BRAIN BLEEDS
  { id: 93, category: "Neuro", q: "An 84-year-old man with a 1-year history of progressive memory loss, disorientation, and personality changes dies after suddenly developing severe headache and right-sided weakness. He had no history of hypertension, cardiovascular disease, or atrial fibrillation. Autopsy shows a large intraparenchymal hemorrhage. Congo red staining of the cerebral blood vessels shows apple-green birefringence under polarized light. Which of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the hemorrhage?", a: "Cerebral amyloid angiopathy. In elderly patients with Alzheimer disease and no HTN, recurrent lobar hemorrhages are caused by amyloid-beta deposition in cerebral vessel walls. Congo red with apple-green birefringence is diagnostic of amyloid." },
  { id: 94, category: "Neuro", q: "A 17-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a high-speed motorcycle accident. He is initially unresponsive with a GCS of 4. He gradually improves over the next several weeks but is left with severe cognitive impairment 2 years later. MRI of the brain performed at the time of the accident showed multiple small hemorrhagic lesions at the gray-white matter junction. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Diffuse axonal injury — caused by shearing forces from rapid deceleration. Characteristic finding is multiple hemorrhagic lesions at the grey-white matter junction on MRI." },
  { id: 95, category: "Neuro", q: "A 30-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after being struck in the temporal region by a baseball. He was briefly unconscious, then \"woke up\" and appeared fine for 2 hours (lucid interval), before rapidly becoming unresponsive. CT of the head shows a biconvex, lens-shaped hyperdensity adjacent to the temporal bone. GCS is 7. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?", a: "Intubation and hyperventilation, followed by craniotomy. Epidural hematoma (rupture of middle meningeal artery) with low GCS requires airway protection first. Hyperventilation decreases CO2, causing cerebral vasoconstriction and reducing intracranial pressure." },
  { id: 96, category: "Neuro", q: "A 78-year-old man with a history of dementia and frequent falls presents to the emergency department after being found confused by his caretaker. He has no history of loss of consciousness. CT of the head without contrast shows a crescent-shaped hyperdensity overlying the right cerebral hemisphere with 8 mm of midline shift. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?", a: "Craniotomy (not observation). Subdural hematoma with significant midline shift requires surgical evacuation. Subdural = rupture of bridging veins, crescent-shaped, no lucid interval." },
  { id: 97, category: "Neuro", q: "A physician is reviewing head CT scans of two patients who both presented with acute headache after head trauma. Patient A has a lens-shaped (biconvex) hyperdensity, while Patient B has a crescent-shaped hyperdensity. Which of the following is the most likely source of bleeding for each patient?", a: "Patient A (biconvex/lens-shaped) = epidural hematoma, rupture of middle meningeal artery. Patient B (crescent-shaped) = subdural hematoma, rupture of bridging (superior cerebral) veins." },
  { id: 98, category: "Neuro", q: "A 58-year-old man with no significant medical history presents to the emergency department with severe headache, confusion, and blood pressure of 220/120 mm Hg. He has no focal neurologic deficits. CT of the head without contrast is normal. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "Hypertensive encephalopathy. Treatment: IV sodium nitroprusside (or other IV antihypertensive) to rapidly but carefully lower BP." },
  { id: 99, category: "Neuro", q: "A 58-year-old man was admitted for hypertensive emergency with blood pressure of 220/120 mm Hg and was treated with IV sodium nitroprusside. Twelve hours later, he develops confusion, metabolic acidosis, and an elevated serum lactate. His skin appears flushed. Which of the following is the most likely complication?", a: "Cyanide toxicity from sodium nitroprusside. Nitroprusside is metabolized to cyanide, which inhibits cytochrome c oxidase (complex IV) of the electron transport chain, causing lactic acidosis." },
  { id: 100, category: "Neuro", q: "A 45-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with the sudden onset of the \"worst headache of her life.\" She also has nuchal rigidity and photophobia. Neurologic examination shows no focal deficits. CT of the head without contrast shows hyperdensity in the basal cisterns. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) — usually due to rupture of a saccular (berry) aneurysm at the ACoM or PCoM. The stiff neck (nuchal rigidity) is caused by meningeal irritation from blood in the subarachnoid space. This commonly confuses students because it mimics meningitis." },
  { id: 101, category: "Neuro", q: "An 80-year-old man with a history of Alzheimer disease and no history of hypertension presents with acute right-sided weakness. This is his third episode of intracerebral hemorrhage in the past 2 years. CT of the head shows a large lobar hemorrhage in the left frontal lobe. Which of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the recurrent hemorrhages?", a: "Cerebral amyloid angiopathy. In Alzheimer patients with recurrent lobar hemorrhages and no HTN, amyloid beta deposition weakens cerebral vessel walls." },
  { id: 102, category: "Neuro", q: "A 31-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after a motor vehicle accident. She is unresponsive with a GCS of 6. Her vital signs show blood pressure of 165/90 mm Hg, respiratory rate of 10 breaths per minute, and heart rate of 55 beats per minute. Which of the following is the most likely mechanism for her hypertension?", a: "Increased intracranial pressure (Cushing reflex/triad). The triad consists of hypertension, bradycardia, and respiratory depression (bradypnea). Elevated ICP compresses intracerebral vessels, triggering sympathetic activation to maintain perfusion." },
  { id: 103, category: "Neuro", q: "A 29-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a motor vehicle accident. Physical examination shows bilateral periorbital ecchymoses (raccoon eyes), bruising over the mastoid processes bilaterally (Battle sign), clear fluid draining from the right ear, and clear fluid draining from the nose. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Basilar skull fracture. Classic tetrad: Battle sign, raccoon eyes, otorrhea (CSF from ear), and rhinorrhea (CSF from nose). Hemotympanum (blood behind the tympanic membrane) may also be present." },
  { id: 104, category: "Neuro", q: "A 50-year-old woman is recovering in the ICU 3 days after surgical clipping of a ruptured anterior communicating artery aneurysm. She develops new-onset left-sided weakness. Transcranial Doppler shows increased flow velocity in the right middle cerebral artery. Which of the following medications should be administered to prevent further complications?", a: "Nimodipine (dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker). Vasospasm is a major delayed complication of SAH (typically days 4-14), and nimodipine is given prophylactically to reduce cerebral vasospasm and ischemic injury." },
  { id: 105, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old woman is admitted for management of severe hyponatremia (serum sodium 110 mEq/L). Her serum sodium is corrected to 132 mEq/L over 6 hours with hypertonic saline. Two days later, she develops difficulty swallowing, inability to speak, and quadriparesis. MRI of the brain shows a symmetric lesion confined to the central pons. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Central pontine myelinolysis (osmotic demyelination syndrome) from overly rapid correction of hyponatremia. Results in locked-in syndrome." },
  { id: 106, category: "Neuro", q: "A 62-year-old man is admitted for management of severe hypernatremia (serum sodium 170 mEq/L). His care team corrects his sodium rapidly with hypotonic saline. The next day, he develops seizures and altered mental status. CT of the head shows diffuse cerebral edema. Which of the following is the mechanism of this complication?", a: "Cerebral edema from overly rapid correction of hypernatremia. Water shifts into brain cells that have accumulated intracellular osmoles to adapt to the chronic hypernatremia." },
  { id: 107, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old man presents with a 3-week history of progressive headache and new-onset seizures. Physical examination shows papilledema and left-sided weakness. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial imaging study?", a: "Contrast-enhanced CT of the head. For suspected brain tumors and abscesses, contrast CT is the initial study of choice." },
  { id: 108, category: "Neuro", q: "A 62-year-old man with a history of hypertension presents with the sudden onset of severe headache and left-sided weakness. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial imaging study?", a: "Non-contrast CT of the head. For suspected intracranial hemorrhage, non-contrast CT is always the initial study. Blood appears hyperdense (white) on CT." },

  // CNS TUMORS
  { id: 109, category: "Neuro", q: "A 44-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematosus presents with a 3-week history of headache, confusion, and left-sided weakness. CT of the head with contrast shows a single ring-enhancing lesion in the right frontal lobe. She is HIV-negative. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Primary CNS lymphoma (NOT Toxoplasmosis). In an immunosuppressed patient who is HIV-negative, autoimmune diseases (SLE, Hashimoto, etc.) increase the risk of primary CNS lymphoma, not Toxo." },
  { id: 110, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 3-year-old boy is brought to the physician because of a 2-month history of failure to thrive and a recent seizure. MRI of the brain shows a large mass in the posterior fossa with both solid (hyperintense) and cystic (hypointense) components. Histologic examination of the resected tumor shows Rosenthal fibers and eosinophilic, corkscrew-shaped filaments. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Pilocytic astrocytoma — the most common brain tumor in children. Has solid and cystic components on MRI. Rosenthal fibers are pathognomonic. Not aggressive." },
  { id: 111, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 54-year-old man presents with a 3-month history of progressive cognitive decline and a seizure today. CT of the head with contrast shows a large, heterogeneous, irregularly enhancing mass crossing the corpus callosum, with areas of necrosis and hemorrhage. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Glioblastoma multiforme (GBM, aka \"butterfly glioma\"). Most common primary brain cancer in adults. Heterogeneous due to necrosis and hemorrhage. Classified as grade IV fibrillary astrocytoma. Crosses midline via corpus callosum." },
  { id: 112, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 16-year-old boy presents with early-onset cataracts and a 6-month history of progressive hearing loss and tinnitus on the left side. MRI of the brain shows a mass at the cerebellopontine angle. His father had bilateral similar masses and was diagnosed with a genetic condition. Which of the following is the most likely underlying genetic condition?", a: "Neurofibromatosis type II (NF2) — autosomal dominant, chromosome 22. Bilateral acoustic schwannomas are the hallmark. In a young patient with unilateral findings, NF2 should still be suspected, especially with family history." },
  { id: 113, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 56-year-old man presents with a 9-year history of progressive right-sided hearing loss and tinnitus. MRI of the brain shows a large enhancing mass at the right cerebellopontine angle. The mass most likely arises from which of the following nerves, and from which cell type?", a: "Vestibulocochlear nerve (CN VIII), arising from Schwann cells (neural crest origin). Vestibular schwannoma (acoustic neuroma) is the most common cerebellopontine angle tumor." },
  { id: 114, category: "Neuro", q: "A 47-year-old man presents with a 6-month history of decreased libido, erectile dysfunction, and progressive bilateral visual field narrowing. Visual field testing shows bitemporal hemianopsia. Serum prolactin is elevated. MRI shows a sellar mass. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Prolactinoma — the most common pituitary tumor in adults. Bitemporal hemianopsia results from compression of the optic chiasm by superior extension of the tumor." },
  { id: 115, category: "Neuro", q: "An 8-year-old boy is brought to the physician because of a 4-month history of headaches, growth failure, and progressive visual field narrowing. Visual field testing shows bitemporal hemianopsia. MRI of the brain shows a suprasellar cystic mass with calcifications. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Craniopharyngioma — the most common pituitary tumor in children. Derived from Rathke pouch (\"roof of the primitive oral cavity/oropharynx\"). Calcifies and contains cholesterol crystals." },
  { id: 116, category: "Neuro", q: "A 3-year-old girl is brought to the emergency department because of a 2-week history of early morning vomiting and unsteady gait. She tends to fall backward when walking. Physical examination shows truncal ataxia with a wide-based gait. MRI of the brain shows a mass in the posterior fossa arising from the cerebellar vermis. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Medulloblastoma of the cerebellar vermis. Aggressive brain tumor of the posterior fossa in children. Vermis location causes truncal ataxia. Can drop metastasize through CSF." },
  { id: 117, category: "Neuro", q: "A pediatric oncologist is asked about the most common primary brain tumor in children. She describes a tumor that appears as a mixed solid and cystic lesion on MRI, contains distinctive eosinophilic corkscrew-shaped filaments on histology, and is generally considered non-aggressive. Which of the following is the most likely tumor?", a: "Pilocytic astrocytoma. Most common primary brain tumor in children. Solid + cystic on MRI. Rosenthal fibers on histology. Low grade and not aggressive." },
  { id: 118, category: "Neuro", q: "A neuro-oncologist is asked which primary brain tumor is most common in adults. She describes a tumor that is highly aggressive, crosses the corpus callosum (\"butterfly\" pattern), has areas of necrosis and hemorrhage on imaging, and is classified as a grade IV astrocytoma. Which of the following is the tumor?", a: "Glioblastoma multiforme (GBM). Most common primary malignant brain tumor in adults. Also classified as grade IV fibrillary astrocytoma." },
  { id: 119, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 5-year-old girl presents with a 1-month history of early morning vomiting, headaches, and difficulty looking upward. CT of the head shows enlargement of the lateral and third ventricles and a 2 cm mass in the region of the pineal gland. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Pinealoma causing Parinaud syndrome (dorsal midbrain syndrome). The mass compresses the superior colliculus and pretectal area, causing paralysis of upward gaze. Morning vomiting suggests increased intracranial pressure from obstructive hydrocephalus." },
  { id: 120, category: "Neuro", q: "A 6-year-old boy is brought to the physician because of opsoclonus (rapid, involuntary, multidirectional eye movements), myoclonus, and hypertension. A chest X-ray shows a mass in the posterior mediastinum. A 24-hour urine collection shows elevated levels of homovanillic acid (HVA) and vanillylmandelic acid (VMA). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Neuroblastoma. Can occur anywhere along the sympathetic chain but classically intra-abdominal or posterior mediastinum. \"Dancing eyes\" = opsoclonus-myoclonus syndrome is a paraneoplastic feature. Diagnosed by elevated urinary HVA and VMA." },
  { id: 121, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old man is diagnosed with a glioblastoma multiforme on brain biopsy. He has significant cerebral edema on imaging. While awaiting definitive surgical and oncologic management, which of the following is the most appropriate initial pharmacologic intervention?", a: "Corticosteroids (dexamethasone). High-dose steroids reduce peritumoral edema and can rapidly improve neurologic symptoms in brain tumor patients." },

  // VISUAL PATHWAY
  { id: 122, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 31-year-old woman with a history of multiple sclerosis presents with a 1-week history of a visual field defect. Visual field testing shows loss of the lower lateral quadrant of the left visual field and the lower lateral quadrant of the right visual field (bilateral inferior lateral loss). Which of the following is the most likely location of the pathology?", a: "Right parietal lobe. Parietal lobe lesions cause contralateral inferior quadrantanopsia (\"pie on the floor\"). Temporal lobe lesions cause contralateral superior quadrantanopsia (\"pie in the sky\")." },
  { id: 123, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 45-year-old woman with a history of non-small cell lung cancer presents with a 2-week history of progressive loss of the left visual field in both eyes. Visual field testing confirms left homonymous hemianopsia. If an MRI of the brain is performed, metastases would most likely be found in which of the following locations?", a: "Right occipital lobe. A left homonymous hemianopsia (loss of the left visual field in both eyes) localizes to the right side of the visual pathway — optic tract, LGN, optic radiations, or occipital cortex." },
  { id: 124, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 52-year-old man with a history of hypertension and atrial fibrillation presents with the sudden onset of painless loss of vision in his right eye. He describes a \"curtain coming down\" over his vision. Fundoscopic examination shows a pale, opaque fundus with a bright red fovea centralis (\"cherry red spot\"). Eight months later, light is shone in the right eye. Which of the following responses is most likely to be observed in the left pupil?", a: "No constriction of the left pupil. The retinal ganglion cells in the right eye have been destroyed by the infarction, so the afferent limb of the pupillary light reflex from the right eye is lost. Neither direct (right) nor consensual (left) response will occur when light is shone in the right eye." },
  { id: 125, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 45-year-old man presents with dilation of the left pupil that was noted after undergoing cranial surgery. The left eye is deviated downward and outward. The right pupil is normal in size and reactive. A cross-section of the cavernous sinus is shown. Which of the following labeled structures is the most likely site of the lesion?", a: "CN III (oculomotor nerve). Lesion causes \"down and out\" eye position + mydriasis (dilated pupil) due to loss of parasympathetic innervation + ptosis due to loss of levator palpebrae superioris function." },
  { id: 126, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 24-year-old man presents because his left pupil does not constrict when light is shone in either eye. However, when light is shone in his left eye, the right pupil constricts normally. Which of the following is the most likely location of the lesion?", a: "Left oculomotor nerve (CN III). The afferent pathway (CN II) is intact because light in the left eye causes right pupil constriction. The efferent pathway to the left eye (CN III parasympathetics) is damaged, so the left pupil cannot constrict." },
  { id: 127, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 69-year-old man with a 50-pack-year smoking history presents with left-sided ptosis, miosis (constricted pupil), and anhidrosis (dry skin) of the left side of the face. A chest X-ray shows a mass at the apex of the left lung. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Pancoast tumor (superior sulcus tumor) of the left lung causing ipsilateral Horner syndrome. The tumor impinges on the superior cervical ganglion/sympathetic chain, disrupting sympathetic innervation to the face (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis)." },
  { id: 128, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A physician shines a light into a patient's right eye and observes both the right and left pupils constrict. The same response is observed when light is shone into the left eye. This test evaluates the functional integrity of which of the following brain structures?", a: "Midbrain (specifically the Edinger-Westphal nucleus and pretectal area). The afferent limb (CN II) carries the signal to the pretectal nucleus, which then activates the Edinger-Westphal nucleus bilaterally, sending efferent signals via CN III to constrict both pupils." },
  { id: 129, category: "Neuro", q: "A 45-year-old woman with a 15-year history of type 2 diabetes presents for a routine eye examination. Fundoscopic examination shows dot-and-blot hemorrhages, hard exudates, cotton wool spots (nerve fiber layer infarcts), and scattered flame-shaped hemorrhages throughout both retinas. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Diabetic retinopathy (non-proliferative/background). Hard exudates = lipid deposits; cotton wool spots = retinal nerve fiber layer ischemia; dot-and-blot = deep retinal hemorrhages." },

  // CAVERNOUS SINUS
  { id: 130, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 34-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a 3-day history of severe headache, high fever (103°F), double vision, swelling around both eyes, and proptosis. He was treated for a sinus infection with oral amoxicillin/clavulanate one week ago. On examination, he has ophthalmoplegia and decreased sensation over the forehead. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Cavernous sinus thrombosis. Sinus infections can ascend to the cavernous sinus via the valveless facial venous system (superior and inferior ophthalmic veins). Usually caused by Staphylococcus aureus. Treat with IV antibiotics + heparin." },
  { id: 131, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 41-year-old woman develops new-onset double vision and difficulty looking laterally with her right eye 2 days after undergoing transsphenoidal surgery for a pituitary adenoma. Which of the following cranial nerves is the most likely to have been injured during the procedure?", a: "Abducens nerve (CN VI). CN VI is the most medial structure within the cavernous sinus and runs closest to the sphenoid sinus, making it the most susceptible to surgical injury during transsphenoidal approaches." },
  { id: 132, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 49-year-old man with a known prolactinoma presents with bitemporal hemianopsia and new-onset inability to abduct his right eye. MRI shows that the tumor has expanded beyond the sella turcica. The patient's new eye finding is most likely caused by compression of which of the following structures?", a: "Right abducens nerve (CN VI). A pituitary tumor expanding laterally from the sella turcica can compress CN VI within the cavernous sinus. Superior extension causes bitemporal hemianopsia via optic chiasm compression." },

  // SEIZURES
  { id: 133, category: "Neuro", q: "A 6-year-old boy is brought to the emergency department because of a witnessed episode of bilateral stiffening and jerking of his extremities lasting 2 minutes. His mother reports that he \"turned blue\" and was unresponsive during the episode. His ECG shows a second-degree AV block. EEG shows no epileptiform activity. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Adams-Stokes attack (cardiac syncope with convulsive-like episode). The arrhythmia leads to transient cerebral hypoperfusion, which can cause seizure-like activity. Normal EEG confirms it is NOT a true seizure." },
  { id: 134, category: "Neuro", q: "A 75-year-old man with a history of myocardial infarction presents because of a 2-year history of recurrent episodes of loss of consciousness associated with bilateral tonic-clonic movements, pallor, and diaphoresis. EEG performed during one episode shows no epileptiform discharges. Telemetry monitoring reveals intermittent ventricular tachycardia. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Convulsive syncope (cardiogenic). The ventricular tachycardia causes transient cerebral hypoperfusion, which can trigger seizure-like motor activity. The absence of epileptiform activity on EEG rules out true epilepsy." },
  { id: 135, category: "Neuro", q: "A 26-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after witnesses observed her fall to the ground and have a generalized tonic-clonic seizure lasting 3 minutes. Upon awakening, she reports that immediately before the seizure, she smelled a foul odor that she could not identify. She has no history of seizures. Which of the following brain regions is the most likely site of origin of her seizure?", a: "Medial temporal lobe. Olfactory auras (perception of a smell that is not present) are classic for temporal lobe epilepsy. Gustatory (taste) or deja vu sensations can also serve as auras from the temporal lobe." },
  { id: 136, category: "Neuro", q: "A 10-month-old boy is brought to the physician because of recurrent episodes of sudden flexion of the trunk, neck, and extremities occurring in clusters, lasting a few seconds each. His development has regressed over the past 2 months. EEG shows a chaotic pattern of high-amplitude spikes and slow waves with no recognizable organization. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "West syndrome (infantile spasms). Classic triad: infantile spasms + hypsarrhythmia on EEG (chaotic, disorganized high-amplitude pattern) + developmental regression. Treatment = ACTH or vigabatrin. X-linked recessive." },
  { id: 137, category: "Neuro", q: "A 13-year-old boy presents with a generalized tonic-clonic seizure. His mother reports that for the past 4 months, she has noticed his left arm jerking involuntarily when he wakes up in the morning. His maternal uncle has epilepsy. EEG shows generalized polyspike-and-wave discharges. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the first-line treatment?", a: "Juvenile myoclonic epilepsy. Characterized by myoclonic jerks (typically upon awakening, hypnagogic/hypnopompic) that progress to generalized tonic-clonic seizures. Onset age 10-16. Treatment = valproic acid." },
  { id: 138, category: "Neuro", q: "A 4-year-old girl is brought to the physician because of near-daily seizures over the past several months that have been refractory to multiple anti-epileptic medications. Her parents report that she has started putting objects in her mouth, making less eye contact, and has lost several developmental milestones. Her seizures often occur during sleep. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Lennox-Gastaut syndrome. Severe childhood-onset epilepsy characterized by near-daily seizures (often multiple types), cognitive decline, and resistance to medication. Hyperoralism (putting objects in mouth) is a sign of cognitive regression. Poor prognosis." },

  // INFECTIONS
  { id: 139, category: "Neuro", q: "A 24-year-old man was treated with IV acyclovir for herpes simplex encephalitis 4 months ago. He now presents with insatiable appetite, inappropriate sexual behavior, and a tendency to put non-food objects in his mouth. He also shows flat affect and difficulty recognizing familiar faces. MRI of the brain shows bilateral damage to the medial temporal lobes. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Kluver-Bucy syndrome — bilateral amygdala destruction. Features: hyperphagia, hypersexuality, hyperorality, visual agnosia, and emotional flattening. Rare but recognized complication of herpes encephalitis." },
  { id: 140, category: "Neuro", q: "A 22-year-old woman who recently returned from a 6-month trip to Central America presents to the emergency department after a witnessed tonic-clonic seizure. She has no prior seizure history. CT of the head shows multiple small, round, cystic lesions scattered throughout the brain parenchyma with some showing calcification — a \"swiss cheese\" appearance. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Neurocysticercosis caused by Taenia solium (pork tapeworm). Multiple cystic brain lesions in a patient from an endemic region. Treatment: albendazole (or praziquantel) + corticosteroids + anti-epileptics." },
  { id: 141, category: "Neuro", q: "A 35-year-old man with HIV and a CD4 count of 47/uL presents with a 3-month history of progressive cognitive decline, personality changes, and difficulty walking. He is compliant with his antiretroviral therapy and TMP-SMX prophylaxis. MRI of the brain shows multiple areas of white matter demyelination without mass effect. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy (PML) caused by JC polyomavirus. Key distinction: USMLE wants \"reactivation of latent infection\" as the mechanism. \"Acute infection in immunocompromised patient\" is the WRONG answer. Patient is on TMP-SMX, which rules out Toxo." },
  { id: 142, category: "Neuro", q: "A 1-year-old boy is brought to the emergency department because of progressive weakness and difficulty feeding over the past 3 days. His mother reports that she recently started giving him honey mixed with cereal. Physical examination shows generalized hypotonia, weak cry, poor suck reflex, and constipation. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Infant botulism — ingestion of Clostridium botulinum spores from honey. Spores germinate in the infant gut and produce botulinum toxin, which inhibits presynaptic acetylcholine release by cleaving SNARE proteins. Presents as the classic \"floppy baby.\"" },
  { id: 143, category: "Neuro", q: "A 13-year-old boy presents with bilateral facial weakness (Bell palsy), constipation, difficulty swallowing, and generalized hypotonia 2 days after eating canned food during a camping trip. He is afebrile. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Foodborne botulism — ingestion of preformed botulinum toxin from improperly canned goods. Treatment = antitoxin (not antibiotics, which are used for wound botulism)." },
  { id: 144, category: "Neuro", q: "A 3-day-old male neonate born at home is brought to the emergency department because of progressive rigidity and arching of the back (opisthotonus). The mother reports that the umbilical cord was cut with a kitchen knife and tied with twine. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of disease in this patient?", a: "Tetanus toxin (from Clostridium tetani) blocks release of inhibitory neurotransmitters GABA and glycine by cleaving SNARE proteins at the presynaptic terminal in the spinal cord, resulting in unopposed excitation and spastic paralysis." },
  { id: 145, category: "Neuro", q: "A newborn is found to have intracranial calcifications diffusely distributed throughout the brain, chorioretinitis, and hydrocephalus on postnatal imaging. The mother had no prenatal care and reports that she has several cats. Which of the following is the most likely congenital infection?", a: "Congenital toxoplasmosis (Toxoplasma gondii). Classic triad: diffuse intracranial calcifications + chorioretinitis + hydrocephalus." },
  { id: 146, category: "Neuro", q: "A newborn is found to have periventricular intracranial calcifications, sensorineural deafness, hepatosplenomegaly, and a diffuse petechial rash (\"blueberry muffin\" rash) on newborn examination. Which of the following is the most likely congenital infection?", a: "Congenital CMV (cytomegalovirus). Most common congenital infection. Periventricular calcifications (vs. diffuse in toxo), sensorineural hearing loss, hepatomegaly, and blueberry muffin rash." },
  { id: 147, category: "Neuro", q: "A newborn is found to have bilateral sensorineural hearing loss on newborn hearing screening. The mother had an uncomplicated pregnancy and no known infections. No other abnormalities are found on physical examination. Which of the following is the most likely cause of the hearing loss?", a: "Congenital CMV. It is the most common infectious cause of congenital sensorineural hearing loss and can present with isolated deafness even without other classic findings." },
  { id: 148, category: "Neuro", q: "A 24-year-old man presents with a 2-day history of painful, grouped vesicles on an erythematous base on his upper lip. He reports having similar episodes several times per year, often triggered by stress or sun exposure. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of this pathogen's recurrent presentation?", a: "Reactivation of latent virus in sensory neurons. HSV-1 lies dormant in the trigeminal ganglion (V2 maxillary branch or V3 mandibular branch) and periodically reactivates, traveling anterogradely along sensory nerves to cause recurrent herpes labialis." },

  // NMJ
  { id: 149, category: "Neuro", q: "A 44-year-old woman who works as an office assistant presents with a 3-month history of double vision, difficulty swallowing, and drooping of her eyelids that worsen as the day progresses. She also reports that she is unable to hold her gaze upward for more than 30 seconds before her eyelids droop. A test is performed in which an intravenous medication produces rapid, dramatic improvement in her symptoms. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Myasthenia gravis. Antibodies against postsynaptic nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. Symptoms worsen with repetitive use and improve with rest. The IV medication is edrophonium (Tensilon test), a short-acting acetylcholinesterase inhibitor." },
  { id: 150, category: "Neuro", q: "A 44-year-old woman presents with a 2-month history of proximal muscle weakness, particularly difficulty climbing stairs and rising from a chair. She denies any double vision or eyelid drooping. She is able to perform sustained upward gaze for 60 seconds without difficulty. EMG shows increasing compound muscle action potential amplitudes with repetitive stimulation. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Lambert-Eaton syndrome. Proximal weakness that IMPROVES with use. If the patient CAN hold upward gaze for 60 seconds, it's LE. If she CANNOT, it's MG. EMG shows incremental response (opposite of MG's decremental response)." },
  { id: 151, category: "Neuro", q: "A 44-year-old woman presents because she has difficulty getting up from a chair. She reports that on the first attempt she cannot stand, but after several attempts she is able to rise. She denies diplopia, ptosis, or dysphagia. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Lambert-Eaton syndrome. Muscle strength that improves with repeated activity is the hallmark. Antibodies against presynaptic voltage-gated calcium channels reduce initial ACh release, but repeated stimulation allows calcium to accumulate and improve transmission." },
  { id: 152, category: "Neuro", q: "A 50-year-old woman presents with fatigable proximal weakness, ptosis, and diplopia. The physician suspects a disorder of neuromuscular transmission, but neither myasthenia gravis nor Lambert-Eaton syndrome is listed among the answer choices. Which of the following is the best answer?", a: "\"Neuromuscular junction\" — when the specific Dx (MG or LE) is not available as an answer choice, the correct answer is the anatomical site." },
  { id: 153, category: "Neuro", q: "A physician is explaining the difference between myasthenia gravis and Lambert-Eaton syndrome to a medical student. What is the target of the autoimmune attack in each condition?", a: "MG = antibodies against postsynaptic nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. LE = antibodies against presynaptic voltage-gated calcium channels (which normally allow calcium influx to trigger ACh vesicle release)." },
  { id: 154, category: "Neuro", q: "A 45-year-old woman is newly diagnosed with myasthenia gravis. A chest X-ray is ordered and shows a widened anterior mediastinum. CT of the chest confirms an anterior mediastinal mass. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis of the mass, and what is the significance?", a: "Thymoma. 10-15% of MG patients have thymoma. After Dx of MG, chest imaging should be done to look for thymoma. Removal of the thymoma (thymectomy) can significantly improve or cure the MG." },
  { id: 155, category: "Neuro", q: "A 60-year-old man with a recent diagnosis of Lambert-Eaton syndrome presents for further workup. Which of the following malignancies is most strongly associated with this condition?", a: "Small cell lung cancer. Lambert-Eaton syndrome is a classic paraneoplastic syndrome of small cell lung cancer." },
  { id: 156, category: "Neuro", q: "A patient with suspected myasthenia gravis is given an IV injection of edrophonium (Tensilon). Her ptosis and diplopia dramatically improve within 30 seconds. A second patient with Lambert-Eaton syndrome receives the same test. Which of the following is the expected response in the second patient?", a: "Minimal or no significant improvement. MG improves dramatically with edrophonium (short-acting AChE inhibitor) because the problem is at the postsynaptic receptor. LE shows less improvement because the problem is presynaptic calcium channel dysfunction." },

  // GBS
  { id: 157, category: "Neuro", q: "A 13-year-old girl presents with a 2-day history of tingling and weakness in her feet that has been progressively ascending to involve her legs. She had a diarrheal illness 2 weeks ago. Physical examination shows 3/5 strength in the lower extremities, absent deep tendon reflexes, and intact sensation. Lumbar puncture shows CSF protein of 95 mg/dL and a leukocyte count of 4/uL. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Guillain-Barre syndrome (GBS). CSF shows albuminocytologic dissociation — elevated protein with normal cell count. Ascending paralysis + areflexia following a preceding infection (classically Campylobacter jejuni, but often no organism is identified)." },
  { id: 158, category: "Neuro", q: "A 24-year-old man presents with a 4-day history of progressive weakness. Physical examination shows weakness of proximal and distal muscles of the lower limbs and weakness of distal muscles of the upper limbs. Deep tendon reflexes are absent throughout. Sensation is intact. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Guillain-Barre syndrome. The pattern of weakness — proximal + distal in lower limbs, distal only in upper limbs — indicates that the ascending paralysis has fully involved the legs but has only partially ascended into the arms." },
  { id: 159, category: "Neuro", q: "A physician is explaining the pathophysiology of Guillain-Barre syndrome to a medical student. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of disease?", a: "T-cell and antibody-mediated destruction of Schwann cells and myelin of peripheral nerves (PNS). This is an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy. Key distinction: MS = CNS/oligodendrocytes; GBS = PNS/Schwann cells." },
  { id: 160, category: "Neuro", q: "A 30-year-old man is diagnosed with Guillain-Barre syndrome after presenting with ascending paralysis and areflexia. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "IVIG (intravenous immunoglobulin) or plasmapheresis. Corticosteroids are NOT effective and are considered a wrong answer for GBS treatment." },

  // CONGENITAL / PEDIATRIC
  { id: 161, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A newborn is found to have a large, fluid-filled sac protruding from the lumbosacral region that transilluminates and contains both meninges and spinal cord tissue. Which of the following embryologic processes was most likely disrupted?", a: "Closure of the caudal neuropore. Myelomeningocele = herniation of meninges AND spinal cord through a vertebral defect. Neural tube closure normally occurs between weeks 3-4 of gestation. Requires adequate folic acid (vitamin B9)." },
  { id: 162, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 23-year-old woman at 20 weeks gestation undergoes a routine ultrasound that shows a fetus with absence of the cranial vault and cerebral hemispheres. Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein is markedly elevated. Which of the following is the mechanism for this condition?", a: "Failure of closure of the rostral neuropore. Anencephaly = absence of brain and calvarium due to failure of the anterior neural tube to close. Elevated AFP in maternal serum and amniotic fluid." },
  { id: 163, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A newborn is noted to have a small tuft of hair on the midline of the lumbar region. Palpation of the area reveals absence of the underlying spinous process. The infant is neurologically normal. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of this condition?", a: "Failure of fusion of the vertebral arches (sclerotomes). This is spina bifida occulta — the mildest form, with only a bony defect and no herniation of meninges or cord. The overlying tuft of hair or dimple is a classic skin marker." },
  { id: 164, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 17-year-old girl presents with chronic headaches and neck pain. She also reports numbness and weakness in her hands. MRI of the brain shows displacement of the cerebellar tonsils more than 5 mm below the foramen magnum. There is also a fluid-filled cavity within the cervical spinal cord. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Chiari I malformation with associated syringomyelia. Chiari I = herniation of cerebellar tonsils through the foramen magnum. Usually presents in teenagers/young adults with headaches and can be associated with a syrinx (fluid-filled cavity) in the spinal cord." },
  { id: 165, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A newborn is found to have a large posterior fossa cyst, absence of the cerebellar vermis, and marked dilation of the fourth ventricle on postnatal MRI. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Dandy-Walker malformation — absent cerebellar vermis + cystic dilation of the fourth ventricle. Can cause obstructive hydrocephalus." },
  { id: 166, category: "Neuro", q: "A 6-month-old boy is brought to the physician because of progressive weakness and difficulty feeding. He was born at term and was initially developing normally. Physical examination shows profound generalized hypotonia (\"floppy infant\"), absent deep tendon reflexes, and fasciculations of the tongue. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis, and which part of the nervous system is primarily affected?", a: "Werdnig-Hoffmann syndrome (spinal muscular atrophy type I). Autosomal recessive degeneration of anterior horn motor neurons. Tongue fasciculations are a buzzword. Anterior horns of the spinal cord are affected." },
  { id: 167, category: "Neuro", q: "A 23-year-old man is found to have an inferonasal defect in the iris of his right eye that gives the appearance of the pupil \"bleeding\" downward. This finding is characteristic of incomplete closure of which of the following embryologic structures?", a: "Choroid (embryonic/optic) fissure, resulting in a coloboma of the iris. This is a feature of CHARGE syndrome (Coloboma, Heart defects, Atresia choanae, Retardation of growth, Genital abnormalities, Ear anomalies)." },
  { id: 168, category: "Neuro", q: "A newborn is noted to have esotropia (inward deviation) of the left eye. The parents ask whether surgery is necessary. The ophthalmologist recommends early surgical correction. Which of the following is the most important reason for correcting strabismus in early childhood?", a: "To allow development of normal binocular vision. If strabismus is not corrected early, the brain will suppress input from the deviated eye, leading to amblyopia (\"lazy eye\") and permanent loss of binocular depth perception." },
  { id: 169, category: "Neuro", q: "A 7-year-old girl is brought to the physician by her parents because of repetitive facial grimacing that has been present for the past 5 months. She has no vocal tics, and her motor examination and mental status are otherwise normal. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?", a: "Schedule a follow-up examination in 3 months (watchful waiting). Dx = provisional tic disorder. Most childhood tics resolve spontaneously. USMLE expects follow-up in 3-6 months as the next best step." },
  { id: 170, category: "Neuro", q: "A 6-year-old girl presents with involuntary, rapid, purposeless movements of her limbs and face 3 weeks after an episode of pharyngitis treated with amoxicillin. Her anti-streptolysin O (ASO) titers are elevated. Which of the following best describes the mechanism of her movement disorder?", a: "Autoimmune-mediated damage to the basal ganglia. This is Sydenham chorea, a manifestation of acute rheumatic fever. Molecular mimicry between streptococcal antigens and basal ganglia neurons leads to antibody cross-reactivity." },

  // VENTRICLES
  { id: 171, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 32-year-old man presents with a 2-month history of intermittent severe headaches and episodes of syncope. MRI of the brain shows hydrocephalus and a round, well-circumscribed cystic lesion at the roof of the anterior third ventricle, near the foramen of Monro. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Colloid cyst. These benign cysts characteristically arise at the roof of the anterior third ventricle near the foramen of Monro. They can cause intermittent obstruction of CSF flow, leading to acute hydrocephalus and sudden death." },
  { id: 172, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 72-year-old man is brought to the physician by his wife because of a 6-month history of progressive unsteady gait, urinary incontinence, and memory problems. CT of the head shows markedly dilated lateral ventricles out of proportion to cortical atrophy. A large-volume lumbar puncture results in temporary improvement of his gait. Which of the following embryologic structures gave rise to the enlarged structures seen on CT?", a: "Telencephalon (of the prosencephalon/forebrain). The dilated lateral ventricles are derived from the telencephalon. This is normal pressure hydrocephalus — classic triad: \"wet\" (incontinence), \"wobbly\" (gait ataxia), \"wacky\" (dementia)." },
  { id: 173, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 7-month-old boy is brought to the emergency department because of repeated vomiting over the past 2 days. His mother found that he had been playing under the kitchen sink near several cleaning products. Physical examination shows a drowsy infant with copious salivation. Which of the following brain structures is most likely responsible for the vomiting, and where is it located?", a: "Area postrema — the chemoreceptor trigger zone for emesis. It is located on the dorsal surface of the medulla at the caudal end of the fourth ventricle. It lacks a blood-brain barrier, allowing it to detect circulating toxins and emetics." },

  // DEMENTIA / NEURODEGENERATIVE
  { id: 174, category: "Neuro", q: "A 61-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department by police after she was found wandering a downtown street, appearing confused and disheveled. She has a broad-based, ataxic gait and horizontal nystagmus. Blood alcohol level and urine drug screen are negative. She appears malnourished. MRI of the brain would most likely show atrophy of which of the following structures?", a: "Mammillary bodies. Dx is Wernicke encephalopathy due to thiamine (B1) deficiency. Mnemonic: A COW = Ataxia, Confusion, Ophthalmoplegia, Wernicke. Classically seen in alcoholics and malnourished patients." },
  { id: 175, category: "Neuro", q: "A 56-year-old man with a long history of alcohol use disorder presents to the emergency department acutely intoxicated. Intravenous thiamine (vitamin B1) is administered. Which of the following symptoms is most significantly reduced by this intervention?", a: "Anterograde amnesia (risk of progression to Korsakoff psychosis). Thiamine treats/prevents Wernicke encephalopathy; if untreated, it can progress to Korsakoff psychosis (irreversible retrograde/anterograde amnesia with confabulations)." },
  { id: 176, category: "Neuro", q: "A 68-year-old man presents to the emergency department with the acute onset of confusion and difficulty forming new memories. He had a transient ischemic attack earlier today. His wife reports that he keeps asking the same questions repeatedly. Which of the following brain structures is most likely affected?", a: "Hippocampus. The hippocampus is very sensitive to ischemic insult and is critical for forming new memories (anterograde memory). It is also a primary site of pathology in Alzheimer disease." },
  { id: 177, category: "Neuro", q: "A 23-year-old man is rescued after a near-drowning episode. He remains comatose for 3 days before recovering. He subsequently has difficulty forming new memories. Histologic examination of a brain biopsy from the affected region shows shrunken neurons with intensely eosinophilic cytoplasm and pyknotic nuclei. Which of the following best describes the histologic finding?", a: "\"Red neurons\" (eosinophilic neuronal necrosis) — the pathologic hallmark of acute hypoxic-ischemic injury. The hippocampi are among the most vulnerable brain regions to ischemia, which is why this patient developed anterograde amnesia." },

  // HEADACHES
  { id: 178, category: "Neuro", q: "A 59-year-old woman presents with a 3-week history of new-onset headache over her right temple, jaw pain when chewing, and proximal muscle stiffness in her shoulders and hips. She also reports malaise and a 5-lb weight loss. ESR is 95 mm/hr. Which of the following is the most appropriate FIRST step in management?", a: "IV methylprednisolone (or high-dose oral prednisone). In temporal arteritis, steroids are given BEFORE biopsy to prevent blindness from ischemic optic neuropathy. Temporal artery biopsy is then performed to confirm the diagnosis." },
  { id: 179, category: "Neuro", q: "A 50-year-old woman presents with a 2-month history of bilateral jaw pain and headaches that worsen with chewing. Physical examination shows tenderness over the temporomandibular joint. ESR is 8 mm/hr (normal). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Temporomandibular joint (TMJ) syndrome. Normal ESR rules out temporal (giant cell) arteritis. If the ESR were elevated, the jaw pain would be \"jaw claudication\" from temporal arteritis." },
  { id: 180, category: "Neuro", q: "A 32-year-old man presents with a diffuse, bilateral, band-like headache that has been present for the past 2 days. The pain is mild to moderate and is relieved by acetaminophen and sleep. He denies nausea, photophobia, or aura. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Tension-type headache. Bilateral, non-pulsatile, band-like quality, without nausea/vomiting or photophobia. Treatment: rest, acetaminophen/NSAIDs, and taper caffeine if applicable." },
  { id: 181, category: "Neuro", q: "A 28-year-old man presents with a 1-week history of severe, unilateral, stabbing headache behind his right eye that wakes him from sleep nightly. Each episode lasts about 30 minutes. He paces around the room during attacks. He also has right-sided lacrimation and nasal congestion. Which of the following is the most appropriate acute treatment, and what medication is used for prophylaxis?", a: "Acute treatment: 100% oxygen (high-flow). Prophylaxis: verapamil (non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker). This is a cluster headache — severe, unilateral, periorbital, with autonomic features, occurring in clusters, typically in young men." },
  { id: 182, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of severe, lancinating pain along her left cheek lasting 10-30 seconds each, triggered by brushing her teeth or a gust of wind. Neurologic examination is normal. Which of the following is the most appropriate prophylactic medication?", a: "Carbamazepine (sodium channel blocker). This is trigeminal neuralgia — brief, severe, electric shock-like pain in the distribution of CN V, triggered by minor stimuli. No acute treatment is needed because episodes are so brief." },
  { id: 183, category: "Neuro", q: "A 30-year-old woman with a history of hypertension comes to the physician because of recurrent unilateral throbbing headaches preceded by seeing zigzag lines. Episodes last several hours and are associated with nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia. She takes lisinopril for blood pressure management. Her physician wants to start a prophylactic medication for the headaches that will also help manage her hypertension. Which of the following is the most appropriate medication?", a: "Propranolol. Migraine prophylaxis = propranolol (beta-blocker), which also treats hypertension. Acute treatment = NSAIDs first, then triptans (serotonin 5-HT1B/1D agonists). Triptans are NOT prophylactic." },
  { id: 184, category: "Neuro", q: "A 23-year-old woman with a history of migraines asks her physician about the chemical mediators that contribute to her headache pain. She wants to understand why the pain is throbbing and localized. Which of the following neuropeptides is most likely a contributor to her migraine pain?", a: "Substance P — a neuropeptide involved in pain signaling and neurogenic inflammation. It is released from trigeminal nerve endings and contributes to vasodilation and the pain of migraines." },

  // VERTIGO / HEARING
  { id: 185, category: "Neuro", q: "A 40-year-old woman presents with recurrent episodes of the room spinning that last 30-60 seconds, sometimes accompanied by nausea and vomiting. The episodes are triggered by rolling over in bed or looking up. The physician tilts her head back and to the right and observes rotary nystagmus after a brief latency. Which of the following is the mechanism of this patient's condition?", a: "Displacement of otoliths (calcium carbonate crystals) into the posterior semicircular canal. Dx = benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV). Diagnosed with the Dix-Hallpike maneuver. Treated with the Epley maneuver (repositions the otolith back to the utricle)." },
  { id: 186, category: "Neuro", q: "A 40-year-old woman presents with a 1-week history of vertigo, tinnitus, and decreased hearing in her left ear following an upper respiratory infection. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Labyrinthitis — viral infection causing inflammation of both the vestibular nerve AND cochlear nerve. Results in vertigo + tinnitus + hearing loss." },
  { id: 187, category: "Neuro", q: "A 40-year-old woman presents with a 1-week history of vertigo following an upper respiratory infection. She denies any hearing loss or tinnitus. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Vestibular neuritis — viral infection causing inflammation of the vestibular nerve ONLY. Results in vertigo WITHOUT hearing loss or tinnitus." },
  { id: 188, category: "Neuro", q: "A 32-year-old man presents with a several-year history of episodes of vertigo, tinnitus, and hearing loss that wax and wane. He has particular difficulty hearing conversations at dinner parties with background noise. His mother had similar symptoms. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Meniere disease. Waxing/waning vertigo + tinnitus + low-frequency hearing loss (difficulty hearing conversations in groups). Mechanism: defective endolymphatic drainage (endolymphatic hydrops). Can have familial component." },
  { id: 189, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old woman presents with a few-month history of intermittent spinning sensation without nausea. When the examiner positions her with her head hanging off the examination table and turned to the left, she develops coarse, rotary nystagmus. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV). Positive Dix-Hallpike maneuver. Need not be associated with vomiting. Treatment: Epley maneuver." },
  { id: 190, category: "Neuro", q: "A 31-year-old man undergoes a caloric reflex test as part of a vestibular workup. Warm water instilled into the left ear produces expected nystagmus. However, warm water instilled into the right ear fails to produce nystagmus. Which of the following is the most likely site of the lesion?", a: "Right-sided vestibular apparatus. The caloric reflex test: warm water causes endolymph movement mimicking ipsilateral head turn, producing contralateral nystagmus. If nystagmus fails to occur, the vestibular apparatus on the stimulated side is dysfunctional." },
  { id: 191, category: "Neuro", q: "A 25-year-old man with a history of intravenous drug use is being treated for infective endocarditis with gentamicin and vancomycin. On hospital day 7, he reports that the room feels like it is spinning and he has difficulty hearing. Which of the following is the most likely cause of his symptoms?", a: "Ototoxicity from gentamicin (aminoglycoside). Aminoglycosides can damage CN VIII, causing sensorineural hearing loss and/or vestibular toxicity (vertigo). Other ototoxic drugs: cisplatin, loop diuretics, aspirin, quinidine." },
  { id: 192, category: "Neuro", q: "A 3-year-old boy is brought to the physician because of ear pain and fever for the past 4 days. Physical examination shows the right pinna is displaced upward and outward, and there is tenderness and erythema over the mastoid process. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?", a: "CT or MRI of the temporal bone. Dx is mastoiditis (complication of acute otitis media). X-ray is insufficient. The fluid collection must be visualized and potentially drained to prevent brain abscess." },

  // PHARMACOLOGY / DRUG SIDE EFFECTS
  { id: 193, category: "Neuro", q: "A 25-year-old man is brought to the emergency department 6 hours after starting haloperidol for a psychiatric condition. He has stiffness in his neck, which is twisted to the right (torticollis), and his eyes are deviated upward. He is afebrile. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "Benztropine (muscarinic receptor antagonist) or diphenhydramine. This is acute dystonia — occurs within hours to days of starting antipsychotics. Key: no fever (differentiates from NMS). Oculogyric crisis + torticollis are classic presentations." },
  { id: 194, category: "Neuro", q: "A 30-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department 12 hours after starting a new antipsychotic medication. She has involuntary upward deviation of both eyes and a stiff, twisted neck. Her temperature is 37.1°C (98.8°F). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Acute dystonia (oculogyric crisis + torticollis). The normal temperature helps distinguish this from neuroleptic malignant syndrome. Treatment: benztropine or diphenhydramine." },
  { id: 195, category: "Neuro", q: "A 35-year-old man is brought to the emergency department because of high fever (41°C/106°F), severe muscle rigidity (\"lead pipe\"), altered mental status, and autonomic instability 5 days after starting haloperidol. Laboratory studies show markedly elevated serum creatine kinase and leukocytosis. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "Dantrolene (inhibits the ryanodine receptor on the sarcoplasmic reticulum, reducing calcium release and muscle contraction). This is neuroleptic malignant syndrome (NMS). Key distinguishing feature from acute dystonia: FEVER." },
  { id: 196, category: "Neuro", q: "A 28-year-old man with schizophrenia was started on risperidone 2 weeks ago. He presents with an irresistible urge to move and reports that he cannot sit still. He is constantly pacing and shifting his weight from foot to foot. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "Propranolol. This is akathisia — subjective restlessness and inability to remain still, a common side effect of antipsychotics." },
  { id: 197, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old woman with schizophrenia has been on haloperidol for 3 months. She now presents with a shuffling gait, cogwheel rigidity, resting tremor, and bradykinesia. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis, and what is the treatment?", a: "Drug-induced Parkinsonism from dopamine D2 receptor blockade. Treatment: amantadine (increases dopamine release) or propranolol. Alternatively, switch to an atypical antipsychotic with less D2 antagonism." },
  { id: 198, category: "Neuro", q: "A 60-year-old woman with schizophrenia has been on chlorpromazine for 15 years. She now presents with involuntary, repetitive movements of her tongue, lips, and jaw, including lip smacking, tongue protrusion, and chewing movements. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Tardive dyskinesia. Late-onset (months to years of antipsychotic use) involuntary orofacial movements. Management: stop the offending antipsychotic + switch to an atypical (clozapine, quetiapine). Valbenazine or deutetrabenazine may be used." },
  { id: 199, category: "Neuro", q: "A 45-year-old woman being treated with metoclopramide for gastroparesis develops involuntary lip smacking and tongue protrusion after 8 months of use. Which of the following properties of metoclopramide best explains this adverse effect?", a: "Dopamine D2 receptor antagonism. Metoclopramide is not an antipsychotic but can cause tardive dyskinesia due to its D2 blocking activity. It can also prolong QT interval and cause hyperprolactinemia." },
  { id: 200, category: "Neuro", q: "A 28-year-old woman with depression is started on a new antidepressant. Two weeks later, she presents to the emergency department after a witnessed generalized tonic-clonic seizure. She has no history of seizures or eating disorders. Which of the following medications is most likely responsible?", a: "Bupropion. It lowers the seizure threshold and is contraindicated in patients with eating disorders (electrolyte abnormalities increase seizure risk). Otherwise a good antidepressant — no sexual side effects, also used for smoking cessation." },
  { id: 201, category: "Neuro", q: "A 52-year-old man with colon cancer being treated with a chemotherapy regimen develops progressive numbness and tingling in his hands and feet over the past 2 months. He also reports difficulty with fine motor tasks. Nerve conduction studies show decreased sensory nerve amplitudes. Which of the following medications is most likely responsible?", a: "Vincristine (or cisplatin). Both are classic causes of chemotherapy-induced peripheral neuropathy. Vincristine inhibits microtubule assembly; cisplatin crosslinks DNA. Both are neurotoxic." },
  { id: 202, category: "Neuro", q: "A 40-year-old woman undergoing treatment for latent tuberculosis with isoniazid presents with a 2-month history of numbness and burning in her feet. She also had one episode of a generalized seizure. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Vitamin B6 (pyridoxine) deficiency caused by isoniazid. Isoniazid depletes pyridoxine, which can cause peripheral neuropathy and seizures. Patients on INH should receive B6 supplementation." },
  { id: 203, category: "Neuro", q: "A 62-year-old man with a 20-year history of type 2 diabetes presents with burning pain, tingling, and numbness in both feet in a stocking-glove distribution. Sensation to light touch and pinprick is decreased bilaterally up to mid-calf. Which of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment for his neuropathic pain?", a: "Tricyclic antidepressant (amitriptyline or nortriptyline). First-line for diabetic neuropathic pain. Second-line options include gabapentin or duloxetine." },
  { id: 204, category: "Neuro", q: "A 72-year-old woman presents with severe, burning pain in a band-like distribution across her left thorax that began 2 weeks after resolution of a vesicular rash in the same area. She reports the pain is excruciating and is triggered by even light touch to the area. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "Gabapentin (or pregabalin). This is post-herpetic neuralgia — neuropathic pain persisting after resolution of herpes zoster (shingles). Antiviral (acyclovir) treats the acute infection; gabapentin treats the chronic neuropathic pain." },
  { id: 205, category: "Neuro", q: "An 82-year-old man with diabetic neuropathy has been taking carbamazepine and gabapentin for several months with no improvement in his pain. His physician decides to switch to a tricyclic antidepressant. Which of the following TCAs is most appropriate for this elderly patient, and why?", a: "Nortriptyline — it has fewer anticholinergic and anti-alpha-1 side effects compared to amitriptyline, making it safer for elderly patients who are more susceptible to confusion, urinary retention, orthostatic hypotension, and falls." },

  // MISCELLANEOUS
  { id: 206, category: "Neuro", q: "A 59-year-old woman with metastatic pancreatic cancer is evaluated in the oncology clinic. She is crying and tells the physician she \"wants to die.\" She rates her abdominal pain as 9/10. She is currently taking acetaminophen as needed. Which of the following is the most likely primary reason for her desire to die?", a: "Inadequate pain control. In cancer patients expressing a wish to die, the first consideration should always be pain management. \"Major depression\" is a wrong answer on NBME when pain is clearly undertreated." },
  { id: 207, category: "Neuro", q: "A 42-year-old woman presents with a 3-month history of insomnia and an uncomfortable crawling sensation in her legs that occurs when lying in bed at night and is temporarily relieved by walking. She has a history of heavy menstrual periods. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial diagnostic test?", a: "Serum iron and ferritin levels. Restless leg syndrome is most commonly caused by iron deficiency. Heavy menstrual periods are a common cause of iron deficiency in premenopausal women." },
  { id: 208, category: "Neuro", q: "A 42-year-old woman presents with a 3-month history of insomnia and restless legs. Her serum iron and ferritin levels are within normal limits. Which of the following is the most appropriate pharmacologic treatment?", a: "Dopamine agonist (pramipexole or ropinirole). When iron stores are normal, dopaminergic therapy is the treatment for restless leg syndrome." },
  { id: 209, category: "Neuro", q: "A 50-year-old man with a long history of restless leg syndrome asks his physician whether the condition puts him at risk for any other diseases. Which of the following conditions is this patient at increased risk of developing?", a: "Parkinson disease. The dopaminergic dysfunction underlying RLS may share pathophysiology with Parkinson disease, and RLS patients have an increased risk of later developing PD." },
  { id: 210, category: "Neuro", q: "A 58-year-old man loses consciousness while shaving his neck in front of the bathroom mirror. He regains consciousness within 30 seconds. In the emergency department, his physical examination and ECG are normal. A tilt-table test shows no abnormalities. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Carotid sinus hypersensitivity. Pressure on the carotid sinus (from shaving, tight collar) triggers an exaggerated vagal response. If the tilt-table test were positive instead, the answer would be vasovagal syncope." },
  { id: 211, category: "Neuro", q: "A 35-year-old man is brought to the emergency department after a motor vehicle accident. CT of the head shows a contusion involving the bilateral frontal lobes. After recovery, his family reports that he has difficulty planning and organizing daily activities, though his memory and language are intact. Which of the following cognitive functions is most likely impaired?", a: "Conceptual planning (executive function). The prefrontal cortex is responsible for planning, decision-making, judgment, and personality. Bilateral frontal lobe damage impairs executive function." },
  { id: 212, category: "Neuro", q: "A 56-year-old man with a history of alcohol use disorder (consuming 12 beers per day) is admitted for an elective surgery. On postoperative day 2, he develops tremulousness, tachycardia, diaphoresis, and visual hallucinations. Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment?", a: "Benzodiazepine (chlordiazepoxide or lorazepam). This is delirium tremens — alcohol withdrawal syndrome occurring 48-96 hours after last drink. Classic vignette: postoperative patient who wasn't screened for alcohol use develops agitation, tremor, autonomic instability, and hallucinations." },
  { id: 213, category: "Neuro", q: "An 87-year-old woman with a history of Alzheimer disease is brought to the emergency department by her caretaker because of increasing confusion and agitation over the past 2 days. She has a low-grade fever of 38.0°C (100.4°F). Her medications include donepezil and memantine. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial diagnostic test to determine the cause of her delirium?", a: "Urinalysis. In elderly patients with baseline dementia, UTI is the most common cause of acute delirium. Always rule out infection (especially UTI) before attributing worsening mental status to progression of dementia." },
  { id: 214, category: "Neuro", q: "A researcher is studying the cellular reservoirs of HIV in the central nervous system. She identifies a cell type that is derived from mesoderm, functions as the resident phagocyte of the CNS, and serves as a major reservoir for the virus. Which of the following cell types is she studying?", a: "Microglia. HIV infects microglia in the CNS, which serve as one of the major cellular reservoirs of the virus. Microglia are the macrophages of the CNS." },
  { id: 215, category: "Neuro", q: "A 51-year-old man with hereditary hemochromatosis presents with decreased libido and fatigue. Laboratory studies show low serum testosterone, low LH, and low FSH, with all other anterior pituitary hormones within normal limits. Which of the following is the most likely location of the iron deposition causing his endocrine dysfunction?", a: "Hypothalamus. The isolated decrease in gonadotropins (LH, FSH) suggests decreased GnRH secretion from the hypothalamus. If the iron were deposited in the anterior pituitary, you would expect multiple hormone deficiencies (panhypopituitarism)." },
  { id: 216, category: "Neuro", q: "A 16-year-old girl is brought to the emergency department after a motor vehicle accident. CT of the head shows a fracture of the sella turcica with transection of the pituitary stalk. Which of the following pituitary hormones is most likely to be INCREASED as a result of this injury?", a: "Prolactin. All hypothalamic hormones are stimulatory EXCEPT dopamine, which tonically INHIBITS prolactin release. Transection of the pituitary stalk removes the inhibitory dopamine signal, causing prolactin to increase." },
  { id: 217, category: "Neuro", q: "A 24-year-old woman presents with a complaint that food has lost its flavor over the past 2 weeks. She was hit in the head by a softball during a game 2 weeks ago. She denies any facial weakness, ear pain, or hearing changes. Neurologic examination is otherwise unremarkable. Damage to which of the following structures most likely explains her symptom?", a: "Cribriform plate (fracture damaging olfactory nerve/CN I). Since smell is required for most of taste perception, anosmia from olfactory nerve damage presents as loss of taste. Key: no Bell's palsy, so this is NOT CN VII injury." },
  { id: 218, category: "Neuro", q: "A 22-year-old woman presents to the emergency department stating that she cannot see out of her left eye since waking up this morning. She appears distressed. Pupillary examination shows equal, round, reactive pupils bilaterally. A swinging flashlight test shows no relative afferent pupillary defect. Visual fields are full to confrontation when tested individually. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Conversion disorder (functional neurological symptom disorder). If she truly had organic vision loss, a Marcus-Gunn pupil (relative afferent pupillary defect) would be present. The intact pupillary response indicates the visual pathway is functioning normally." },
  { id: 219, category: "Neuro", q: "A 38-year-old woman presents with hoarseness of voice that began 1 week ago. She reports increased stress at work and a recent argument with her spouse. Laryngoscopy shows normal vocal cord anatomy and mobility. Neurologic examination is unremarkable. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Conversion disorder. Hoarseness with normal laryngeal anatomy and function in the context of psychosocial stressors suggests functional (non-organic) etiology." },
  { id: 220, category: "Neuro", q: "A 20-year-old woman presents with a 1-year history of difficulty releasing her grip after shaking hands and progressive weakness in her hands. She also notes that her hair is thinning at the front of her scalp. Physical examination shows frontal balding, percussion myotonia, and difficulty relaxing her grip after making a fist. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Myotonic dystrophy (type 1). Autosomal dominant CTG trinucleotide repeat disorder. Classic features: myotonia (difficulty relaxing muscles), frontal balding, cataracts, cardiac conduction defects, and testicular atrophy in males." },
  { id: 221, category: "Neuro", q: "A 30-year-old man presents with excessive daytime sleepiness, sudden episodes of muscle weakness triggered by laughter (cataplexy), and vivid hallucinations as he falls asleep. Which of the following neurotransmitters is most likely deficient?", a: "Orexin (hypocretin). Narcolepsy is caused by loss of orexin-producing neurons in the lateral hypothalamus. Orexin normally promotes wakefulness." },
  { id: 222, category: "Neuro", q: "A 25-year-old woman presents with excessive daytime sleepiness and episodes in which she suddenly falls asleep during conversations. She also reports episodes of sudden muscle weakness in her legs triggered by strong emotions. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?", a: "Polysomnography (sleep study) followed by a multiple sleep latency test (MSLT). Polysomnography rules out other sleep disorders; MSLT confirms narcolepsy by demonstrating rapid onset of REM sleep." },
  { id: 223, category: "Neuro", q: "A 28-year-old man is diagnosed with narcolepsy with cataplexy. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial pharmacologic treatment for his excessive daytime sleepiness?", a: "Modafinil (a wakefulness-promoting agent that is a dopamine reuptake inhibitor and also promotes release of orexin from the hypothalamus). First-line for the sleepiness component of narcolepsy." },
  { id: 224, category: "Neuro", q: "A 22-year-old woman with major depressive disorder is started on fluoxetine. The therapeutic benefit of this medication is primarily due to its effects on neurons located in which of the following brain regions?", a: "Raphe nuclei (located in the brainstem). The raphe nuclei contain serotonin-producing neurons. Fluoxetine (an SSRI) increases serotonin availability by blocking its reuptake at these synapses." },
  { id: 225, category: "Neuro", q: "A 57-year-old woman with invasive gallbladder cancer presents with a 3-week history of severe, intractable left-sided abdominal and back pain. She has failed conservative pain management. She is scheduled for a cordotomy to relieve her pain. Which of the following spinal cord tracts should be surgically targeted?", a: "Right (contralateral) spinothalamic tract. The spinothalamic tract carries pain and temperature and crosses at the level of the spinal cord. To relieve left-sided pain, the right spinothalamic tract must be cut (anterolateral cordotomy)." },
  { id: 226, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 42-year-old woman presents with a 4-month history of abnormal tingling that started in her right hand and has progressively spread to involve the right arm and right side of her face. MRI of the brain shows a lesion in the left cerebral hemisphere. The lesion is most likely located in which of the following cortical areas?", a: "Left postcentral gyrus (primary somatosensory cortex — posterior to the central sulcus). The somatosensory homunculus maps hand laterally and face inferiorly. A lesion here causes contralateral sensory deficits." },
  { id: 227, category: "Neuro", q: "A 72-year-old woman presents with the sudden onset of decreased pain and temperature sensation on the left side of her face and the right side of her body, paralysis of the left vocal cord, and loss of the left gag reflex. Which of the following brain structures is most likely affected?", a: "Left dorsolateral medulla (lateral medullary syndrome/Wallenberg). CN IX (gag reflex afferent) and CN X (vocal cords via recurrent laryngeal nerve) dysfunction + crossed pain/temperature deficits." },
  { id: 228, category: "Neuro", q: "A 61-year-old woman undergoes successful surgical repair of a leaking anterior communicating artery aneurysm. A postoperative CT scan shows widening of the subarachnoid space. Which of the following is the most likely cause of this finding?", a: "Decreased absorption of CSF through the arachnoid granulations (villi). Blood in the subarachnoid space from the SAH can obstruct the arachnoid granulations, reducing CSF absorption and causing communicating hydrocephalus." },
  { id: 229, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 42-year-old woman is struck in the left eye by a golf ball. She presents with diplopia, periorbital swelling, enophthalmos, impaired upward gaze, and decreased sensation over the left cheekbone. Imaging shows a left orbital floor fracture. Entrapment of which of the following muscles best explains her symptoms?", a: "Inferior rectus and inferior oblique. An orbital floor (blowout) fracture can trap the inferior rectus (limiting upward gaze) and inferior oblique. The infraorbital nerve (V2) runs along the orbital floor, explaining the cheek numbness." },
  { id: 230, category: "Neuroanatomy", q: "A 3-month-old boy is noted to have moderate esotropia (inward deviation of one eye). A pediatric ophthalmologist explains to the parents that if left untreated, the child will not develop normal depth perception because of disrupted competitive interactions in the visual cortex during the critical period. Calcium entry through which of the following receptors mediates this competitive process?", a: "NMDA (glutamate) receptors. Activity-dependent synaptic refinement in the developing visual cortex requires NMDA receptor activation, which allows calcium influx and strengthens active synapses via long-term potentiation (LTP)." },

  // SPINAL CORD COMPRESSION
  { id: 231, category: "Neuro", q: "A 68-year-old man with a history of prostate cancer presents with new-onset lower back pain and bilateral leg weakness over the past week. Physical examination shows hyperreflexia in the lower extremities and a positive Babinski sign bilaterally. MRI of the spine shows an enhancing epidural mass at the T8 level. Which of the following is the most appropriate FIRST step in management?", a: "Intravenous corticosteroids (dexamethasone). For suspected spinal cord compression from metastatic disease, steroids should be given FIRST (before MRI, if not yet obtained, or before radiation/surgery). If steroids are not listed, then MRI is the next best step." },
  { id: 232, category: "Neuro", q: "A 65-year-old woman with a history of breast cancer presents with progressively worsening back pain, weakness in both legs, and urinary retention over the past 5 days. Physical examination shows decreased sensation below the nipple line and brisk reflexes in both lower extremities. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial pharmacologic intervention?", a: "Intravenous high-dose dexamethasone. Metastatic spinal cord compression requires emergent corticosteroids to reduce edema around the tumor, followed by radiation therapy or surgical decompression." },
  { id: 233, category: "Neuro", q: "A 65-year-old woman with a history of metastatic breast cancer presents with a 1-month history of worsening lower back pain, a palpable suprapubic mass, decreased anal sphincter tone, and pain with fist percussion over the lumbar vertebrae. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Metastases to the cauda equina (below the conus medullaris). Decreased sphincter tone + late urinary retention (overflow incontinence from distended bladder) + LMN signs point to cauda equina involvement rather than cord compression." },

  // MENINGITIS WORKUP
  { id: 234, category: "Neuro", q: "A physician is evaluating a patient with suspected meningitis and is considering whether to perform a lumbar puncture or obtain a CT of the head first. Which of the following are the four indications for obtaining a CT before LP?", a: "1) Focal neurologic signs, 2) Seizure, 3) Papilledema or inability to visualize the optic fundi, 4) Altered mental status / decreased Glasgow Coma Scale. These suggest possible mass lesion where LP could cause herniation." },
  { id: 235, category: "Neuro", q: "A lumbar puncture is performed on a patient with suspected bacterial meningitis. CSF analysis shows glucose 25 mg/dL (serum glucose 100 mg/dL), protein 200 mg/dL, and a white cell count of 2,500/uL with 90% polymorphonuclear cells. Which of the following best describes these CSF findings?", a: "Bacterial meningitis: decreased glucose (bacteria consume it), elevated protein (inflammation), elevated neutrophils (PMNs). Classic ratio: CSF glucose < 2/3 of serum glucose." },
  { id: 236, category: "Neuro", q: "A lumbar puncture is performed on a college student with headache, fever, and nuchal rigidity. CSF analysis shows normal glucose, mildly elevated protein, and a white cell count of 300/uL with 95% lymphocytes. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Viral (aseptic) meningitis. Normal glucose + normal or mildly elevated protein + lymphocytic predominance." },
  { id: 237, category: "Neuro", q: "A lumbar puncture is performed on a 45-year-old man with HIV and a CD4 count of 80/uL who presents with headache and fever. CSF analysis shows decreased glucose, elevated protein, and a white cell count of 50/uL with 90% lymphocytes. India ink preparation shows encapsulated organisms. Which of the following best describes these CSF findings?", a: "Fungal meningitis (Cryptococcus neoformans). CSF pattern is similar to bacterial (low glucose, high protein) but with lymphocytes instead of neutrophils. Latex agglutination is preferred over India ink for diagnosis." },
  { id: 238, category: "Neuro", q: "A 25-year-old man presents with fever, confusion, and seizures. MRI of the brain shows abnormal signal in the bilateral temporal lobes. Lumbar puncture shows numerous RBCs in the CSF, elevated protein, normal glucose, and a lymphocytic pleocytosis. EEG shows periodic lateralizing epileptiform discharges over the temporal regions. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Herpes simplex encephalitis (HSV-1). RBCs in CSF = temporal lobe hemorrhagic necrosis (pathognomonic). Treatment: IV acyclovir. CT is often negative early; MRI and EEG are more sensitive." },
  { id: 239, category: "Neuro", q: "A 40-year-old man with HIV and a CD4 count of 50/uL presents with a 2-week history of headache and fever. Lumbar puncture shows elevated opening pressure. CSF shows low glucose, elevated protein, and lymphocytic pleocytosis. India ink staining is negative. Which of the following tests is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?", a: "Latex agglutination (cryptococcal antigen test). It is more sensitive than India ink for diagnosing Cryptococcal meningitis and is preferred when listed. Mucicarmine staining (red stain for the capsule) can also be performed." },

  // CAROTID WORKUP
  { id: 240, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old man with a history of hypertension (BP 150/90 mm Hg) presents 2 hours after an episode of transient right-sided weakness and slurred speech that resolved completely within 45 minutes. CT of the head is normal. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in the workup?", a: "Carotid duplex ultrasonography. In a patient with TIA and hypertension, the priority is to look for a carotid plaque that may have embolized to the brain." },
  { id: 241, category: "Neuro", q: "An 80-year-old man with good blood pressure control (110/70 mm Hg) presents after an episode of transient left-sided weakness that resolved within 1 hour. CT of the head is normal. Carotid duplex ultrasound shows no significant stenosis. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in the workup?", a: "ECG (to look for atrial fibrillation). In an elderly patient with TIA and good BP/no carotid disease, AF with mural thrombus is the likely embolic source. If ECG is normal sinus rhythm, do a Holter monitor — AF is often paroxysmal." },
  { id: 242, category: "Neuro", q: "A 55-year-old man with well-controlled blood pressure presents for a routine physical. On auscultation, a bruit is heard over the right carotid artery. He has no neurologic symptoms. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step?", a: "Carotid duplex ultrasonography. A carotid bruit warrants evaluation for carotid artery stenosis even in an asymptomatic patient." },
  { id: 243, category: "Neuro", q: "A 65-year-old man with a recent TIA undergoes carotid duplex ultrasound showing 85% stenosis of the right internal carotid artery. He is currently on aspirin and a statin. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?", a: "Carotid endarterectomy. For symptomatic patients (TIA/stroke) with >70% stenosis, or asymptomatic patients with >80% stenosis, surgical endarterectomy is indicated. Below these thresholds, medical management alone is appropriate (statin + antiplatelet)." },

  // MUSCLE
  { id: 244, category: "Neuro", q: "A 50-year-old woman presents with a 2-month history of progressive difficulty climbing stairs and raising her arms above her head. Laboratory studies show an elevated ESR and a markedly elevated serum creatine kinase (CK). She also has a faint heliotrope rash over her eyelids. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Dermatomyositis (or polymyositis if no rash). Proximal muscle weakness + elevated CK + elevated ESR. The heliotrope rash over the eyelids is specific to dermatomyositis." },
  { id: 245, category: "Neuro", q: "A 50-year-old woman presents with bilateral shoulder and hip stiffness that is worst in the morning and improves with activity over the course of the day. She also reports fatigue and malaise. Laboratory studies show an elevated ESR of 60 mm/hr. CK is normal. She has no proximal muscle weakness on examination. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR). Key distinguishing features from polymyositis: NO proximal muscle weakness + NORMAL CK. PMR has stiffness and pain but preserved strength." },
  { id: 246, category: "Neuro", q: "A 48-year-old woman presents with a 3-month history of progressive proximal muscle weakness, difficulty swallowing, and muscle tenderness. Laboratory studies show elevated ESR and CK. Her physician suspects an inflammatory myopathy. Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?", a: "Anti-Jo1 or anti-Mi2 antibodies, or EMG with nerve conduction studies. These help confirm the diagnosis of polymyositis/dermatomyositis. Muscle biopsy may follow for definitive diagnosis. No specific diagnostic test exists for PMR." },
  { id: 247, category: "Neuro", q: "A 38-year-old woman presents with a 2-week history of headache, facial flushing, and swelling of the neck and arms. She notes that symptoms worsen when bending forward. Fundoscopic examination shows bilateral papilledema. A chest X-ray shows a large anterior mediastinal mass. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?", a: "Superior vena cava (SVC) syndrome. NBME wants \"obstruction of venous return to the heart.\" SVC compression (often from lung cancer or lymphoma/thymoma) causes facial/upper extremity edema, JVD, and headache. Positive Pemberton sign." },
];

export default neuroQuestions;
